{"title_page": "Bonaventure Cemetery", "text_new": "{{Infobox cemetery\n|name        = Bonaventure Cemetery\n|image       = bonaventure.jpg\n|imagesize   = 200px\n|caption     = \n|established = 1846<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n|country     = \n|location    = 330 Bonaventure Road<br>[[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"CityNotes\" /> \n|coordinates = {{coord|32|2|38|N|81|2|44|W|region:US-GA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}<ref name=FindAGrave>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=cr&GScid=32916&CRid=32916&pt=Bonaventure%20Cemetery&|title=Bonaventure Cemetery|accessdate=2008-08-15}}</ref>\n|type        = Public municipal\n|owner       = City of Savannah<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n|size        = {{convert|160|acre|m2|sing=on|sigfig=3}}<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n|graves      = <!-- how many gravesites -->\n|website     = <!-- official website -->\n|findagraveid=32916\n|nrhp = \n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Bonaventure Cemetery\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = hd    | nocat = yes  \n  | image = \n  | caption = \n| locmapin = USA Georgia#USA\n  | architect = Urban, Henry; et al.\n  | architecture = \n  | added = February 2, 2001\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum = 01000035<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''Bonaventure Cemetery''' is a [[rural cemetery]] located on a scenic bluff of the [[Wilmington River (Georgia)|Wilmington River]], east of [[Savannah, Georgia]].<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />  The cemetery became famous when it was featured in the 1994 novel ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'' by [[John Berendt]], and in the movie, directed by [[Clint Eastwood]], based on the book.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1270983541.html?dids=1270983541:1270983541&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+23%2C+1997&author=ELEANOR+RANDOLPH&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Graveyard+turns+into+tourist+haunt%3B+A+bestseller+has+brought+busloads+of+the+curious%2C+and+a+perilous+fame%2C+to+an+old+cemetery+in+Savannah.&pqatl=google|title=Graveyard turns into tourist haunt; A bestseller has brought busloads of the curious, and a perilous fame, to an old cemetery in Savannah |last=Randolph|first= Eleanor |date=January 23, 1997|work=Los Angeles Times|page=5|accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref> It is the largest of the city's municipal cemeteries, containing nearly {{convert|160|acre|km2}}.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n\nThe entrance to the cemetery is located at 330 Bonaventure Road.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />  Immediately inside the gates is the large and ornate \"Gaston's Tomb\".\n\n==History==\nThe cemetery is located on the former site of [[Bonaventure Plantation]], originally owned by [[Colonel]] John Mullryne. On March 10, 1846, [[Commodore (United States)|Commodore]] [[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]], sold the {{convert|600|acre|km2|adj=on}} plantation and its private cemetery to Peter Wiltberger.  Major William H. Wiltberger, the son of Peter, formed the Evergreen Cemetery Company on June 12, 1868. On July 7, 1907 the City of Savannah purchased the Evergreen Cemetery Company, making the cemetery public and changing the name to Bonaventure Cemetery.<ref name=\"CityNotes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/f88b2a9460d8675b8525704c006921d4/e3d89c83dac0d9e585257035006681c3?OpenDocument|title=Bonaventure Cemetery|accessdate=2008-08-15|publisher=City of Savannah|work=City of Savannah Department of Cemeteries|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615042142/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/f88b2a9460d8675b8525704c006921d4/e3d89c83dac0d9e585257035006681c3?OpenDocument|archivedate=2008-06-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1867 [[John Muir]] began his ''Thousand Mile Walk''<ref>[http://www.sierraclub.org/john_muir_exhibit/writings/a_thousand_mile_walk_to_the_gulf/ A Thousand Mile Walk to the Gulf]</ref> to Florida and the Gulf. In October he sojourned for six days and nights in the Bonaventure cemetery, sleeping upon graves overnight, this being the safest and cheapest accommodation that he could find while he waited for money to be expressed from home. He found the cemetery even then breathtakingly beautiful and inspiring and wrote a lengthy chapter upon it, \"Camping in the Tombs.\"\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Part of the grounds was cultivated and planted with live-oak (''[[Quercus virginiana]]''), about a hundred years ago, by a wealthy gentleman who had his country residence here But much the greater part is undisturbed. Even those spots which are disordered by art, Nature is ever at work to reclaim, and to make them look as if the foot of man had never known them. Only a small plot of ground is occupied with graves and the old mansion is in ruins.\n\nThe most conspicuous glory of Bonaventure is its noble avenue of live-oaks. They are the most magnificent planted trees I have ever seen, about fifty feet high and perhaps three or four feet in diameter, with broad spreading leafy heads. The main branches reach out horizontally until they come together over the driveway, embowering it throughout its entire length, while each branch is adorned like a garden with ferns, flowers, grasses, and dwarf palmettos.\n\nBut of all the plants of these curious tree-gardens the most striking and characteristic is the so-called Long Moss ([[Spanish moss|''Tillandsia usneoides'']]). It drapes all the branches from top to bottom, hanging in long silvery-gray skeins, reaching a length of not less than eight or ten feet, and when slowly waving in the wind they produce a solemn funereal effect singularly impressive.\n\nThere are also thousands of smaller trees and clustered bushes, covered almost from sight in the glorious brightness of their own light. The place is half surrounded by the salt marshes and islands of the river, their reeds and sedges making a delightful fringe. Many bald eagles roost among the trees along the side of the marsh. Their screams are heard every morning, joined with the noise of crows and the songs of countless warblers, hidden deep in their dwellings of leafy bowers. Large flocks of butterflies, flies, all kinds of happy insects, seem to be in a perfect fever of joy and sportive gladness. The whole place seems like a center of life. The dead do not reign there alone.\n\nBonaventure to me is one of the most impressive assemblages of animal and plant creatures I ever met. I was fresh from the Western prairies, the garden-like openings of Wisconsin, the beech and maple and oak woods of Indiana and Kentucky, the dark mysterious Savannah cypress forests; but never since I was allowed to walk the woods have I found so impressive a company of trees as the [[Tillandsia|tillandsia-draped]] oaks of Bonaventure.\n\nI gazed awe-stricken as one new-arrived from another world. Bonaventure is called a graveyard, a town of the dead, but the few graves are powerless in such a depth of life. The rippling of living waters, the song of birds, the joyous confidence of flowers, the calm, undisturbable grandeur of the oaks, mark this place of graves as one of the Lord\u2019s most favored abodes of life and light.\"<br>\n- [[wikisource:A Thousand-Mile Walk To The Gulf/Chapter 4|\"Camping in the Tombs,\" from ''A Thousand Mile Walk'']]\n</blockquote><gallery mode=\"packed-hover\">\nFile:Bonaventure cemetery - theus7351.JPG|Theus tomb\nFile:Bonaventure cemetery - baldwin 7356.JPG|Baldwin tomb\nFile:BoneventureCemetry21.jpg|\"Gracie\"\nFile:BoneventureCemetry28.jpg|Lawton grave\nFile:GenRHAnderson.jpg|R H Anderson\nFile:AndersonFamilyGravesite.jpg|Anderson Family Gravesite\nFile:SpanAmWarVets.jpg|Spanish-American War Veterans\nFile:Bonaventure Cemetery, Savannah, GA, US (22).jpg|Statue\n</gallery>\n\n==Operations==\nCitizens of Savannah and others may purchase interment rights in Bonaventure.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n\nThe cemetery is open to the public daily from 8:00&nbsp;a.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m. There is no admission fee.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n\nAdjacent to Bonaventure Cemetery is the privately owned and newer Forest Lawn Cemetery and Columbarium.\n\n==Department of Cemeteries==\nThe main office of the City of Savannah's Department of Cemeteries is located on the Bonaventure Cemetery grounds in the Bonaventure Administrative Building at the entrance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf|title=Cemeteries Department Home Page}}</ref>\n\n==Bonaventure Historical Society==\nThe cemetery became the subject of a non-profit group, the Bonaventure Historical Society, in May 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonaventurehistorical.org|title=Bonaventure Historical Society}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADA4BCE62CE3AA&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Group enjoys working to keep up grounds of old Savannah cemetery |date=November 2, 1999 |work=The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution |page=B4|accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB864755364102681500?mod=googlewsj|title=Good and Evil and Cookies Help Savannah Charities |last=Greene|first=Kelly|work=The Wall Street Journal|date= May 28, 1997|accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref> The group has compiled an index of the burials at the cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MT&s_site=macon&p_multi=MT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB76C7F5BC3031F&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=New index helps preserve data from Savannah graveyard|date=August 26, 2000|work=Macon Telegraph|page=2 B |accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==''Bird Girl''==\nThe cover photograph for the best-selling book ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'', taken by [[Jack Leigh]], featured an evocative sculpture of a young girl, the so-called ''[[Bird Girl]]'', that had been in the cemetery, essentially unnoticed, for over 50 years. After the publication of the book, the sculpture was relocated from the cemetery in 1997 for display in [[Telfair Museums]] in Savannah. In late 2014, the statue was moved to a dedicated space in the Telfair Museums' [[Jepson Center for the Arts]] on West York Street, in Savannah.<ref>{{cite web|title=Telfair Museums Jepson Center|url=http://www.telfair.org/visit/jepson/|website=telfair.org|publisher=TELFAIR MUSEUMS|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n*[[Samuel B. Adams]], interim Justice of the Supreme Court of Georgia<ref name=\"GHS\">{{cite web|url=http://ghs.galileo.usg.edu/ghs/view?docId=ead/MS%201559-ead.xml|title=Samuel Barnard Adams papers|publisher=Georgia Historical Society|access-date=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Conrad Aiken]], novelist and poet\n*[[Robert H. Anderson|Robert Houstoun Anderson]] (1835-1888), 2nd Lieutenant US Army, General CSA Army, Chief of Police City of Savannah \n*[[Middleton Barnwell]], bishop\n*[[Edythe Chapman]], actress\n*[[Jack Leigh]], photographer, author \n*[[Hugh W. Mercer]], Civil War Army officer and Confederate general \n*[[Johnny Mercer]], singer/songwriter and great-grandson of Hugh W. Mercer\n*[[James Neill (actor)|James Neill]], actor \n*[[John Allen Croskeys Royall]] (1860\u20131959), president, [[New England Oil Company]]\n*[[Marie Louise Scudder Myrick|Marie Louise Scudder-Myrick]] (1854-1934), First Female Owner, Editor, Publisher of a Southern US Newspaper (1895), ''The Americus Times-Recorder''.\n*[[Josiah Tattnall (Senator)|Josiah Tattnall]] (1765-1803), Senator, General, and Georgia Governor\n*[[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1795-1871), Commodore USN, Captain CSA Navy\n*[[Edward Telfair]], governor\n*[[Francis Bland Tucker|F. Bland Tucker]], Episcopal minister and hymn writer \n*[[John Walz]] (1844-1922), sculptor\n*[[Gracie Watson]], famous statue at her gravesite, 6 years old\n*[[Claudius Charles Wilson]] (1831\u20131863), Civil War Confederate brigadier General \n*[[Rosa Louise Woodberry]] (1869\u20131932), journalist, educator\n*[[Bartholomew Zouberbuhler]] (1719\u20131766), early Presbyterian minister<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eR7SAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA379&lpg= | title=Journal of Presbyterian History| year=1906}}</ref>\n*Spanish\u2013American War Veterans from Worth Bagley Camp #10 in Section K.  It is the nation's second-largest area dedicated to those killed in the Spanish\u2013American War.<ref>Historic Bonaventure Cemetery:  Photographs from the Collection of the Georgia Historical Society by Amie Marie Wilson and Mandi Dale Johnson.</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bonaventurehistorical.org/must-see= | title=Bonaventure Historical Society Cemetery Tour App|}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|A Thousand-Mile Walk To The Gulf/Chapter 4|John Muir's writing about Bonaventure Cemetery}}\n*[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~langolier/bonaventure.html Pictures from Bonaventure Cemetery]\n* {{Commons category-inline|Bonaventure Cemetery}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Landmarks in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Chatham County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Geography of Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Chatham County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Rural cemeteries]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cemetery\n|name        = Bonaventure Cemetery\n|image       = bonaventure.jpg\n|imagesize   = 200px\n|caption     = \n|established = 1846<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n|country     = \n|location    = 330 Bonaventure Road<br>[[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"CityNotes\" /> \n|coordinates = {{coord|32|2|38|N|81|2|44|W|region:US-GA_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}<ref name=FindAGrave>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=cr&GScid=32916&CRid=32916&pt=Bonaventure%20Cemetery&|title=Bonaventure Cemetery|accessdate=2008-08-15}}</ref>\n|type        = Public municipal\n|owner       = City of Savannah<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n|size        = {{convert|160|acre|m2|sing=on|sigfig=3}}<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n|graves      = <!-- how many gravesites -->\n|website     = <!-- official website -->\n|findagraveid=32916\n|nrhp = \n{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Bonaventure Cemetery\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = hd    | nocat = yes  \n  | image = \n  | caption = \n| locmapin = USA Georgia#USA\n  | architect = Urban, Henry; et al.\n  | architecture = \n  | added = February 2, 2001\n  | governing_body = Local\n  | refnum = 01000035<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2009a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n'''Bonaventure Cemetery''' is a [[rural cemetery]] located on a scenic bluff of the [[Wilmington River (Georgia)|Wilmington River]], east of [[Savannah, Georgia]].<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />  The cemetery became famous when it was featured in the 1994 novel ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'' by [[John Berendt]], and in the movie, directed by [[Clint Eastwood]], based on the book.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1270983541.html?dids=1270983541:1270983541&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jan+23%2C+1997&author=ELEANOR+RANDOLPH&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Graveyard+turns+into+tourist+haunt%3B+A+bestseller+has+brought+busloads+of+the+curious%2C+and+a+perilous+fame%2C+to+an+old+cemetery+in+Savannah.&pqatl=google|title=Graveyard turns into tourist haunt; A bestseller has brought busloads of the curious, and a perilous fame, to an old cemetery in Savannah |last=Randolph|first= Eleanor |date=January 23, 1997|work=Los Angeles Times|page=5|accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref> It is the largest of the city's municipal cemeteries, containing nearly {{convert|160|acre|km2}}.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n\nThe entrance to the cemetery is located at 330 Bonaventure Road.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />  Immediately inside the gates is the large and ornate \"Gaston's Tomb\".\n\n==History==\nThe cemetery is located on the site of a [[Plantations in the American South|plantation]] originally owned by [[Colonel]] John Mulryne. On March 10, 1846, [[Commodore (United States)|Commodore]] [[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]], sold the {{convert|600|acre|km2|adj=on}} Bonaventure Plantation and its private cemetery to Peter Wiltberger.  Major William H. Wiltberger, the son of Peter, formed the Evergreen Cemetery Company on June 12, 1868. On July 7, 1907 the City of Savannah purchased the Evergreen Cemetery Company, making the cemetery public and changing the name to Bonaventure Cemetery.<ref name=\"CityNotes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/f88b2a9460d8675b8525704c006921d4/e3d89c83dac0d9e585257035006681c3?OpenDocument|title=Bonaventure Cemetery|accessdate=2008-08-15|publisher=City of Savannah|work=City of Savannah Department of Cemeteries|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615042142/http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf/f88b2a9460d8675b8525704c006921d4/e3d89c83dac0d9e585257035006681c3?OpenDocument|archivedate=2008-06-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 1867 [[John Muir]] began his ''Thousand Mile Walk''<ref>[http://www.sierraclub.org/john_muir_exhibit/writings/a_thousand_mile_walk_to_the_gulf/ A Thousand Mile Walk to the Gulf]</ref> to Florida and the Gulf. In October he sojourned for six days and nights in the Bonaventure cemetery, sleeping upon graves overnight, this being the safest and cheapest accommodation that he could find while he waited for money to be expressed from home. He found the cemetery even then breathtakingly beautiful and inspiring and wrote a lengthy chapter upon it, \"Camping in the Tombs.\"\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Part of the grounds was cultivated and planted with live-oak (''[[Quercus virginiana]]''), about a hundred years ago, by a wealthy gentleman who had his country residence here But much the greater part is undisturbed. Even those spots which are disordered by art, Nature is ever at work to reclaim, and to make them look as if the foot of man had never known them. Only a small plot of ground is occupied with graves and the old mansion is in ruins.\n\nThe most conspicuous glory of Bonaventure is its noble avenue of live-oaks. They are the most magnificent planted trees I have ever seen, about fifty feet high and perhaps three or four feet in diameter, with broad spreading leafy heads. The main branches reach out horizontally until they come together over the driveway, embowering it throughout its entire length, while each branch is adorned like a garden with ferns, flowers, grasses, and dwarf palmettos.\n\nBut of all the plants of these curious tree-gardens the most striking and characteristic is the so-called Long Moss ([[Spanish moss|''Tillandsia usneoides'']]). It drapes all the branches from top to bottom, hanging in long silvery-gray skeins, reaching a length of not less than eight or ten feet, and when slowly waving in the wind they produce a solemn funereal effect singularly impressive.\n\nThere are also thousands of smaller trees and clustered bushes, covered almost from sight in the glorious brightness of their own light. The place is half surrounded by the salt marshes and islands of the river, their reeds and sedges making a delightful fringe. Many bald eagles roost among the trees along the side of the marsh. Their screams are heard every morning, joined with the noise of crows and the songs of countless warblers, hidden deep in their dwellings of leafy bowers. Large flocks of butterflies, flies, all kinds of happy insects, seem to be in a perfect fever of joy and sportive gladness. The whole place seems like a center of life. The dead do not reign there alone.\n\nBonaventure to me is one of the most impressive assemblages of animal and plant creatures I ever met. I was fresh from the Western prairies, the garden-like openings of Wisconsin, the beech and maple and oak woods of Indiana and Kentucky, the dark mysterious Savannah cypress forests; but never since I was allowed to walk the woods have I found so impressive a company of trees as the [[Tillandsia|tillandsia-draped]] oaks of Bonaventure.\n\nI gazed awe-stricken as one new-arrived from another world. Bonaventure is called a graveyard, a town of the dead, but the few graves are powerless in such a depth of life. The rippling of living waters, the song of birds, the joyous confidence of flowers, the calm, undisturbable grandeur of the oaks, mark this place of graves as one of the Lord\u2019s most favored abodes of life and light.\"<br>\n- [[wikisource:A Thousand-Mile Walk To The Gulf/Chapter 4|\"Camping in the Tombs,\" from ''A Thousand Mile Walk'']]\n</blockquote><gallery mode=\"packed-hover\">\nFile:Bonaventure cemetery - theus7351.JPG|Theus tomb\nFile:Bonaventure cemetery - baldwin 7356.JPG|Baldwin tomb\nFile:BoneventureCemetry21.jpg|\"Gracie\"\nFile:BoneventureCemetry28.jpg|Lawton grave\nFile:GenRHAnderson.jpg|R H Anderson\nFile:AndersonFamilyGravesite.jpg|Anderson Family Gravesite\nFile:SpanAmWarVets.jpg|Spanish-American War Veterans\nFile:Bonaventure Cemetery, Savannah, GA, US (22).jpg|Statue\n</gallery>\n\n==Operations==\nCitizens of Savannah and others may purchase interment rights in Bonaventure.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n\nThe cemetery is open to the public daily from 8:00&nbsp;a.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m. There is no admission fee.<ref name=\"CityNotes\" />\n\nAdjacent to Bonaventure Cemetery is the privately owned and newer Forest Lawn Cemetery and Columbarium.\n\n==Department of Cemeteries==\nThe main office of the City of Savannah's Department of Cemeteries is located on the Bonaventure Cemetery grounds in the Bonaventure Administrative Building at the entrance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.savannahga.gov/cityweb/cemeteriesweb.nsf|title=Cemeteries Department Home Page}}</ref>\n\n==Bonaventure Historical Society==\nThe cemetery became the subject of a non-profit group, the Bonaventure Historical Society, in May 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonaventurehistorical.org|title=Bonaventure Historical Society}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AT&p_theme=at&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EADA4BCE62CE3AA&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=Group enjoys working to keep up grounds of old Savannah cemetery |date=November 2, 1999 |work=The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution |page=B4|accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB864755364102681500?mod=googlewsj|title=Good and Evil and Cookies Help Savannah Charities |last=Greene|first=Kelly|work=The Wall Street Journal|date= May 28, 1997|accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref> The group has compiled an index of the burials at the cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=MT&s_site=macon&p_multi=MT&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB76C7F5BC3031F&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=New index helps preserve data from Savannah graveyard|date=August 26, 2000|work=Macon Telegraph|page=2 B |accessdate=2009-10-31}}</ref>\n\n==''Bird Girl''==\nThe cover photograph for the best-selling book ''[[Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil]]'', taken by [[Jack Leigh]], featured an evocative sculpture of a young girl, the so-called ''[[Bird Girl]]'', that had been in the cemetery, essentially unnoticed, for over 50 years. After the publication of the book, the sculpture was relocated from the cemetery in 1997 for display in [[Telfair Museums]] in Savannah. In late 2014, the statue was moved to a dedicated space in the Telfair Museums' [[Jepson Center for the Arts]] on West York Street, in Savannah.<ref>{{cite web|title=Telfair Museums Jepson Center|url=http://www.telfair.org/visit/jepson/|website=telfair.org|publisher=TELFAIR MUSEUMS|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable burials==\n*[[Samuel B. Adams]], interim Justice of the Supreme Court of Georgia<ref name=\"GHS\">{{cite web|url=http://ghs.galileo.usg.edu/ghs/view?docId=ead/MS%201559-ead.xml|title=Samuel Barnard Adams papers|publisher=Georgia Historical Society|access-date=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Conrad Aiken]], novelist and poet\n*[[Robert H. Anderson|Robert Houstoun Anderson]] (1835-1888), 2nd Lieutenant US Army, General CSA Army, Chief of Police City of Savannah \n*[[Middleton Barnwell]], bishop\n*[[Edythe Chapman]], actress\n*[[Jack Leigh]], photographer, author \n*[[Hugh W. Mercer]], Civil War Army officer and Confederate general \n*[[Johnny Mercer]], singer/songwriter and great-grandson of Hugh W. Mercer\n*[[James Neill (actor)|James Neill]], actor \n*[[John Allen Croskeys Royall]] (1860\u20131959), president, [[New England Oil Company]]\n*[[Marie Louise Scudder Myrick|Marie Louise Scudder-Myrick]] (1854-1934), First Female Owner, Editor, Publisher of a Southern US Newspaper (1895), ''The Americus Times-Recorder''.\n*[[Josiah Tattnall (Senator)|Josiah Tattnall]] (1765-1803), Senator, General, and Georgia Governor\n*[[Josiah Tattnall|Josiah Tattnall, Jr.]] (1795-1871), Commodore USN, Captain CSA Navy\n*[[Edward Telfair]], governor\n*[[Francis Bland Tucker|F. Bland Tucker]], Episcopal minister and hymn writer \n*[[John Walz]] (1844-1922), sculptor\n*[[Gracie Watson]], famous statue at her gravesite, 6 years old\n*[[Claudius Charles Wilson]] (1831\u20131863), Civil War Confederate brigadier General \n*[[Rosa Louise Woodberry]] (1869\u20131932), journalist, educator\n*[[Bartholomew Zouberbuhler]] (1719\u20131766), early Presbyterian minister<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eR7SAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA379&lpg= | title=Journal of Presbyterian History| year=1906}}</ref>\n*Spanish\u2013American War Veterans from Worth Bagley Camp #10 in Section K.  It is the nation's second-largest area dedicated to those killed in the Spanish\u2013American War.<ref>Historic Bonaventure Cemetery:  Photographs from the Collection of the Georgia Historical Society by Amie Marie Wilson and Mandi Dale Johnson.</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.bonaventurehistorical.org/must-see= | title=Bonaventure Historical Society Cemetery Tour App|}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|A Thousand-Mile Walk To The Gulf/Chapter 4|John Muir's writing about Bonaventure Cemetery}}\n*[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~langolier/bonaventure.html Pictures from Bonaventure Cemetery]\n* {{Commons category-inline|Bonaventure Cemetery}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:Landmarks in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Chatham County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Geography of Savannah, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Historic districts on the National Register of Historic Places in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Chatham County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Rural cemeteries]]\n", "name_user": "Seasider53", "label": "safe", "comment": "linked Bonaventure Plantation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonaventure_Cemetery"}
{"title_page": "Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument", "text_new": "{{short description|Monument in Brooklyn, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Coord|40.6918|N|73.9756|W|display=title}}\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1    = Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument from southwest.jpg\n| width1    = 211\n| caption1  = Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument (2013)\n| image2    = Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument top from southwest.jpg\n| width2    = 206\n| caption2  = [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]]'s brazier at the top\n}}\n[[File:Program of the Dedicatory Ceremonies of the Prison Ship Martyrs Monument (1908).jpg|thumb|225px|Program for the dedication ceremonies, November 14, 1908]]\n\nThe '''Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument''' in [[Fort Greene Park]], in the [[New York City]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[Brooklyn]], is a memorial to the more than 11,500 American [[prisoners of war]] who died in captivity aboard sixteen British [[prison ship]]s during the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref name=nyt1995 /> The remains of a small fraction of those who died on the ships are interred in a [[crypt]] beneath its base. The ships included [[HMS Jersey (1736)|HMS ''Jersey'']], ''Scorpion'', ''Hope'', ''Falmouth'', ''Stromboli'', ''Hunter'', and others.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 568\u20139.</ref><ref name=wilson89>Wilson, James Grant. [https://books.google.com/books?id=KFUOAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA8& ''The memorial History of the City of New-York, From its First Settlement to the Year 1892''], vol. IV New York:New-York History Company, 1893, pp. 8\u20139. Accessed: January 22, 2012</ref>\n\nTheir remains were first gathered and interred in 1808. In 1867 landscape architects [[Frederick Law Olmsted]] and [[Calvert Vaux]], designers of [[Central Park]] and [[Prospect Park (Brooklyn)|Prospect Park]], were engaged to prepare a new design for Washington Park as well as a new crypt for the remains of the prison ship martyrs.<ref name=parks>[http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/monuments/1222 \"Fort Greene Park: Prison Ship Martyrs Monument: History\"] on the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] website</ref> In 1873, after development near the [[Brooklyn Navy Yard]] uncovered the remains, they were moved and re-interred in a crypt beneath a small monument. Funds were raised for a larger monument, which was designed by noted architect [[Stanford White]]. Constructed of granite, its single Doric column {{convert|149|ft|m}} in height sits over the crypt at the top of a {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} 33-step staircase. At the top of the column is an eight-ton bronze [[brazier]], a funeral urn, by sculptor [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]]. President-elect [[William Howard Taft]] delivered the principal address when the monument was dedicated in 1908.\n\n==Context==\n\n===Remains of deceased prisoners===\n{{main|Prisoners in the American Revolutionary War}}\n\nDuring the Revolutionary War, the British maintained a series of prison ships in New York Harbor and jails on shore for prisoners of war.<ref>Andros, Thomas.  \"The old Jersey captive: Or, A narrative of the captivity of Thomas Andros ... on board the old Jersey prison ship at New York, 1781. In a series of letters to a friend.\" W. Peirce. 1833.</ref><ref>Lang, Patrick J..  \"The horrors of the English prison ships, 1776 to 1783, and the barbarous treatment of the American patriots imprisoned on them.\" Society of the Friendly Sons of Saint Patrick, 1939.</ref> Due to brutal conditions, more Americans died in British jails<ref>{{cite news |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030193/1903-12-07/ed-1/seq-6/#date1=1836&sort=relevance&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&index=6&words=skelatons&proxdistance=5&date2=1922&ortext=&proxtext=skelaton&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=2 |page=2 |newspaper=[[New York Tribune]] |title=Skeletons Found in City Hall Park |date=December 7, 1903 |quote=On December 7, 1903 workman found the remains of two men at the site of the Old hall of Records at City Hall Park in New York City; it had been used as a prison during the American Revolution.}}</ref> and prison ships in [[New York Harbor]] than in all the battles of the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Banks |first1=James Lenox |title=Prison ships in the Revolution: New facts in regard to their management |year=1903}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-18520115\">{{cite news |last1=Hanford |first1=William H. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1852/11/16/75121675.pdf |title=Incidents of the Revolution: Recollections of the Old Sugar House Prison |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=January 15, 1852 |accessdate=February 11, 2011}}</ref>  The British disposed of the bodies of the dead from the jails and ships by quick interment or throwing the bodies overboard. Following the end of the war in 1783, the remains of those who died on the prison ships<ref name=\"abbyw.com\">McDonnell, Sharon. [http://www.abbyw.com/fortgreenepark.org/pages/ASP_0307_PrisonShips.pdf \"Revolutionary Martyrs\"] ''American Spirit'' (March/April 2007)</ref> were neglected, left to lie along the Brooklyn shore on [[Wallabout Bay]], a rural area little visited by New Yorkers.<ref>Cray,  \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", p. 573.</ref> On January 21, 1877,  the ''New York Times'' reported that the dead came from all parts of the nation and \"every state of the Union was represented among them.\"<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1877/01/21/80361957.pdf \"The Prison-Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (January 21, 1877)</ref>\n\nOfficials of the local [[Dutch Reformed Church]] met with resistance from the property owner when they sought to remove the bones to their churchyard.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", p. 574.</ref> Nathaniel Scudder Prime reported on \"skulls and feet, arms and legs sticking out of the crumbling bank in the wildest disorder\".<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Long Island: From Its First Settlement by Europeans to the Year 1845 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=elEOAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Edwin G. Burrows described the skulls on the coast \"as thick as pumpkins in an autumn cornfield\".<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Edwin G. Burrows|last=Burrows|first=Edwin G.|title=Forgotten Patriots: The Untold Story of American Prisoners During the Revolutionary War|year=2008|publisher=Basic Books|location=New York|isbn=0786727047}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Giddens|first=Elizabeth|title=Memorials and the Forgotten|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/04/nyregion/when-memorials-outlast-the-sentiment-behind-them.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|accessdate=February 10, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 2, 2011}}</ref> During construction at the Naval Yards, workers were not sure what to do with the bones, and they started to fill casks and boxes. They were reburied on the grounds of the nearby John Jackson estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmm.org/martyrs.html|title=Memorial to martyred mariners rededicated|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nEventually, \"near twenty [[hogsheads]] full of bones were collected by the indefatigable industry of John Jackson, esq. the committee of Tammany Society, and other citizens, to be interred in the vault.\"<ref name=dewitt>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UVBAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=Wallabout+Committee+monument&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage |page=85 |title=An Historical Account of the Interment of the Remains of the American Martyrs at the Wallabout |first=Benjamin|last=De Witt |year=1808 |publisher=Frank, White, and Co. |accessdate=January 13, 2013 }}</ref> The monument's dedication plaque estimates that 11,500 prisoners of war died in the prison ships, but others estimate the number to be as high as 18,000.<ref>{{cite journal |authorlink=Edwin G. Burrows |last=Burrows |first=Edwin G. |url=https://lihj.cc.stonybrook.edu/2012/articles/the-prisoners-of-new-york/ |title=The Prisoners of New York |journal=Long Island History Journal |year=2011 |volume=22 |number=2}}</ref>\n\n===Political resolve===\nThe movement to commemorate the dead only took off when political differences between Federalists and [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republicans]] deepened in the last years of the eighteenth century and the latter took up the question of a memorial in response to the Federalist erection of a statue of George Washington in 1803.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 575\u20138.</ref> The [[Tammany Society]], headed by Benjamin Romaine<ref>[http://www.nysoclib.org/ledger/people/romaine_benjamin.html \"Benjamin Romaine\"] on the New York Society Library website</ref><ref>[http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~promaine/martyrs/Monument-timeline.html \"Timeline of the Burial of the Prison Ship Martyrs and Benjamin Romaine\"] on the RootsWeb website</ref> was created and grew into a Republican organization. On February 10, 1803 Republican Congressman [[Samuel L. Mitchill]] asked the federal government to erect a monument to the fallen, but had no success<ref name=dewitt /><ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 578\u20139.</ref> They then turned their efforts to a grand ceremonial re-interment of the prisoners' remains, emphasizing less the construction of a monument than something more suited to the common man. Tammany formed the Wallabout Committee in January 1808. Their efforts took strength from renewed anti-British feeling stemming from [[Embargo Act of 1807|British incidents]] in 1806 and 1807. Finally, when President Thomas Jefferson enacted the [[Embargo Act]] of 1808, Tammany and the Republicans used their plans for a re-interment as part of their campaign to bolster anti-British sentiment.\n\n==Precursor vaults and monuments==\n\n===First vault and monument===\nOn April 13, 1808, there was a ceremony to lay the cornerstone of a planned vault. A grand ceremony of re-interment followed on May 26, 1808.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 584\u20135.</ref> The state voted to provide the Tammany Society $1,000 to build a monument. The Society pocketed the money and the monument was never built.<ref>{{cite book|last=Allen|first=Oliver E.|title=The Tiger: The Rise and Fall of Tammany Hall|date=1993|publisher=Addison-Wesley Publishing Company|p=[https://archive.org/details/tigerrisefalloft00alle/page/21 21]|isbn=0-201-62463-X|url=https://archive.org/details/tigerrisefalloft00alle/page/21|url-access=registration}}</ref> A small square building stood above the 1808 vault with an eagle mounted at the point of the roof.  It was located on a triangular plot of land near the Brooklyn Navy Yard waterfront (Wallabout Bay) in what is now called [[Vinegar Hill, Brooklyn|Vinegar Hill]].<ref name=\"fort-greene.com\">[http://fort-greene.com/monument.html \"The Prison Ship Martyrs Monument\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903225606/http://fort-greene.com/monument.html |date=September 3, 2013 }} on the Fort Greene Park Conservancy website</ref> A wooden fence with thirteen posts and bars painted with the names of the original thirteen states was erected in front. At the entrance through the fence, an inscription said: \"Portal to the tomb of 11,500 patriot prisoners, who died in dungeons and prison-ships, in and about the City of New-York, during the Revolution.\"<ref>McCulloch, J. R. [https://books.google.com/books?id=U3IrAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA474& ''A Dictionary, Geographical, Statistical, and Historical of the Countries, Places, and Principal Natural Objects in the World'']. New York: Harper & Brothers, 1852, vol. 1, p. 474. Accessed January 17, 2012</ref> The remains were put in long coffins made of bluestone. Extra space was provided in case more bones were discovered during continuing renovations in the Brooklyn Navy Yard.<ref name=hinds>{{cite news|last=Hinds|first=Kate|title=Fort Greene Park's Prison Ships Martyrs Monument|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2010/may/31/fort-greene-parks-prison-ships-martyrs-monument/|accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=WNYC|date=May 31, 2010}}</ref> Little was done to repair or maintain the vault and eventually the original monument was in a state of disrepair and neglect.<ref name=\"fort-greene.com\"/> In 1839, Benjamin Romaine purchased the land where the Martyrs were buried, in a tax sale from [[Henry Reed Stiles]] for $291.08.<ref name=nyt1>{{cite web|url=http://nytelecom.vo.llnwd.net/o15/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/172.pdf |title=Martyr's Monument/Monument Lot Memo Report on Archeological Investigations |date=December 19, 2003 |accessdate=January 13, 2013 |page=1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230232257/http://nytelecom.vo.llnwd.net/o15/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/172.pdf |archivedate=December 30, 2013 }}</ref> Later that year on July 4, 1839, Benjamin Romaine made an appeal for support (governmental or civic) to build a monument. In this appeal, Romaine talked about the monument and his intention to use his Revolutionary War pension for the monument.<ref>Childs, C.C. & Childs, E., Jr. \"The tomb of the martyrs\". ''Benjamin Romaine's Review'' (July 4, 1839)</ref> On January 31, 1844, Benjamin Romaine died and was also interred in the crypt as he had been a prisoner of war on the ships.\n\n[[File:Fgpark.jpg|thumb|350px|The new monument in Washington Park, Brooklyn]]\n\n===Second vault and monument===\nLater in the nineteenth century, the idea of erecting of a monument on the vault site attracted only occasional interest until 1873 when an appropriation of $6,500<ref name=\"bklyn-genealogy-info.com\">[http://bklyn-genealogy-info.stevemorse.org/Cemetery/old/1873.revol.html \"Revolutionary Martyrs\"] ''[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]'' (January 18, 1873) and (January 8, 1888)</ref> was established for a new mausoleum. The new {{convert|25|by|11|ft|adj=on}} brick mausoleum in Fort Greene Park, then known as Washington Park, was constructed.<ref name=wilson89 /><ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", p. 588.</ref> The new mausoleum was constructed of Portland granite embellished with pillars and fret work of polished Aberdeen stone. The front of the tomb had the following inscription: \"SACRED TO THE MEMORY, OF OUR SAILORS, SOLDIERS AND CITIZENS, WHO SUFFERED AND DIED ON BOARD BRITISH PRISON SHIPS IN THE WALLABOUT DURING THE AMERICAN REVOLUTION\".<ref name=\"bklyn-genealogy-info.com\"/> On June 18, 1873, the first tomb was emptied of bones and they were moved to this tomb.<ref name=nyt1/> The bones remained here until interest was again built and a new monument could be constructed.\n\n==Third monument==\n\n===History===\n\n====Planning and construction====\nThe Fort Greene Chapter of the DAR was formed in 1896 in Brooklyn to foster the construction of a \"suitable memorial to the memory of martyrs, civilian, military and naval, who perished in the noisome prison ships anchored in the Wallabout Bay during the Revolutionary War\". The group quickly partnered with the Old Brooklynites to increase focus on the memorial.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abbyw.com/fortgreenepark.org/pages/ASP_0307_PrisonShips.pdf |title=Revolutionary Martyrs |first1=Sharon |last1=McDonnell |publisher=Fort Greene Park |format=[[PDF]] |accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the discovery of additional bones in the Brooklyn Naval Yard in 1899, interest in establishing a significant monument was again renewed.<ref>\"Fort Greene Historic District Designation Report\"</ref><ref>C.B.B. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1903/05/24/102001740.pdf \"The Prison Ship Martyrs\" (letter to the editor)] ''[[New York Times]]'' (May 23, 1903)</ref> On June 16, 1900, the bones found during additional excavations in the Brooklyn Navy Yard were interred in the crypt with full military honors. The boxes were reported to be oak, {{convert|5|ft|spell=in}} long and {{convert|2|ft|spell=in}} wide.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1900/06/17/102600886.pdf \"Prison Ship Martyrs Buried in Fort Greene] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 17, 1900)</ref> On June 19, 1900, the Brooklyn Eagle reported that a committee had been appointed to build a larger memorial to replace the current one. Due to the work of this committee, funds for a new monument were finally considered and raised.\n\nFunding for a larger monument came from all levels of government. On June 28, 1902, a joint resolution of the House and Senate appropriated $100,000 for the memorial construction under the provision that an additional $100,000 be raised from other sources.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1902/06/28/101274900.pdf \"For Monument toPrison Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 28, 1902)</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1902/06/17/101955518.pdf \"To Prison Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 17, 1902)</ref> In the following months, New York State provided $25,000, and New York City $50,000, while private contributions provided another $25,000.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead,\" 589</ref><ref>\"Gleanings from American Art Centers,\" ''Brush and Pencil'', vol. 12, no. 4 (July 1903), 291\u20132</ref> Following funds being established, the Prison Ship Martyrs Association was incorporated in Albany on May 9, 1903<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1903/05/10/105052692.pdf \"For Prison Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (May 10, 1903)</ref> to oversee the work and the renowned architect [[Stanford White]] (1853\u20131906) of the architectural firm of [[McKim, Mead & White]] was commissioned to design it. The contract for construction of the monument was awarded to Carlin Construction Company under the project supervision of Lieut. Col. [[William Louis Marshall|W. L. Marshall]].<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1907/03/12/106743624.pdf \"Monument Contract Let. Carlin Construction Company to Build Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (March 12, 1907)</ref>\nIn 1776, Fort Greene Park was the site of [[Fort Putnam]], one of a series of defenses built on the high land in Brooklyn. The construction was supervised by Colonel [[Rufus Putnam]] and the purpose was to protect New York from the British.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n====Dedication ceremony====\nThe dedication ceremony on November 15, 1908, included a parade with 15,000 participants, including military and National Guard units, veterans, and civic organizations, including representatives of [[Tammany Hall|Tammany Hall Society]] in their first parade since the Civil War. President-elect [[William Howard Taft]], Secretary of War [[Luke Edward Wright|Luke E. Wright]], New York Governor [[Charles Evans Hughes]], New Jersey Governor [[John Franklin Fort|Franklin Fort]], and Delaware Governor [[Preston Lea]] watched along with approximately twenty thousand spectators as \"the enormous flag draping the Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument on the highest point of Fort Greene Park, Brooklyn, was allowed to slide slowly to the ground from its heighth {{sic}} of 198 feet in the air\".<ref name=taft-and-hughes /> The ceremony was opened with a prayer delivered by Rev. [[S. Parkes Cadman]], followed by a poem composed and read by the occasion's poet laureate [[Thomas Walsh (poet)|Thomas Walsh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nation Honors Martyred Dead|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53948216|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=November 15, 1908|page=6|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The principal address was delivered by Taft.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1908/11/14/104768987.pdf |title=Martyrs' Monument Day in Brooklyn |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=November 14, 1908 |accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref> He set out in detail the treatment of American prisoners and of the dead he said: \"They died because of the cruelty of their immediate custodians and the neglect of those who, in higher authority, were responsible for their detention.\"<ref name=\"taft-and-hughes\" /> He carefully described British culpability:\n\n{{quote|I do not wish to be understood as charging that these conditions were due to the premeditations of the English commanders in chief or to the set purposes of anyone in authority having to do with the fate of the unfortunate men whose bravery and self-sacrifice this monument records. Such a charge would make the British commanders human monsters. The conditions were the result of neglect, not design.}}\n\nHe discussed the treatment of prisoners of war throughout history and praised the recent [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|Hague Convention]] on the rights of prisoners of war and the recent [[First Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]] in which \"both parties exceeded, in the tenderness and the care which they gave to the prisoners of the other, the requirements of the Hague Convention\".<ref name=taft-and-hughes>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1908/11/15/104812779.pdf |title=Taft and Hughes at Martyrs' Shaft |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=November 15, 1908 |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the initial dedication, the Society of Old Brooklynites has hosted an annual memorial for the martyrs every year since President Taft dedicated the monument in 1908.<ref name=nyt1995/>\n\n====Repeated neglect and restoration====\nIn February 1914, one of the eagles was stolen. The thieves sold it as scrap metal for $24.<ref name=stolen>{{cite news|title=Huge Bronze Eagle Stolen from Park|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1914/02/02/101430037.pdf |accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=February 2, 1914}}</ref> The thieves broke the eagle from the granite base, rolled it down the slope and loaded it on a three-wheeled push cart, leaving tracks which the police were able to follow. When police found it at a recycling yard, the wings of the eagle had already been removed and partially melted.<ref name=stolen/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CRMbAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=Prison+Ship+Martyrs%27+Monument&source=bl&ots=f7DHKyPbb7&sig=JoMlNfx88X6YQDBGDsdqvQkS_V0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6d_9U-K4EJO6ogSN1oBI&ved=0CFQQ6AEwCThG#v=onepage&q=Prison%20Ship%20Martyrs'%20Monument&f=false|title=Documents of the Assembly of the State of New York|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eagle by Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument.jpg|left|thumb|One of four bronze eagles by Adolph Weinman at the restored monument site.]]\n\nBy 1921, the beacon was out. The twin helix stairways to the top of the monument, which visitors once paid a dime to climb,<ref name=\"articles.nydailynews.com\">[http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-11-15/news/17910101_1_freedom-fighters-new-yorker-forgotten-patriots \"Memorial to Revolutionary War patriots shines anew in Brooklyn\"] ''[[New York Daily News]]'' (November 14, 2008)</ref> were closed. Until then, visitors could go to the top to get impressive views of Manhattan. In 1923, the bronze door to the crypt was \"battered from its hinges\" by vandals and the crypt was exposed. The ''[[New York Times]]'' report of the incident described how the monument provided a play area for neighborhood children: \"[A] score of children, white and black, who live in the neighborhood were using the granite coping of the walls leading to the crypt as a sort of 'chute the chutes.' The color line was sharply drawn. The slope of one side was used by the negro children while the slope of the other side amused the whites. The children of neither hue were concerned with the crime. They realized vaguely that something unusual had taken place, but it was not important enough to them to stop their daily sport.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Smash Bronze Door to Martyrs' Tomb|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1923/05/12/105994187.pdf |accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 12, 1923}}</ref> However, neglect and damage to the park required it to be renovated. The memorial had become so scarred by vandals and unkempt from lack of proper maintenance as to present a dilapidated appearance. Work was done to clean and preserve the site. A staircase and elevator were installed inside the large column, and it was reopened in 1937 by Park Commissioner [[Robert Moses]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Historic Fort Greene Park is Reopened; Ceremony Marks Restoration of Area|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1937/06/30/94394948.pdf|accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 30, 1937}}</ref> Again, the park was neglected and restoration work was required. It began in 1948 to \"keep the shrine from falling apart\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Shaft of Martyrs Saved in Brooklyn|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1949/07/10/84273243.pdf|accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 10, 1949}}</ref> The staircase and elevator, however, were both removed in 1949.<ref name=nyt1995 /><ref name=parks /> In 1966, the eagles were removed and went missing until 1974.\n\nIn the ensuing years, however, the park slowly decayed again and, by the 1970s, graffiti covered much of the base of the monument and vandalism was taking its toll.<ref>[http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/monument.html \"The Monument\"] on the Prison Ship Martyrs Association website</ref> After being vandalized repeatedly, the four eagles were removed for repairs in 1966 and restored when $251,000 was spent to repair the monument about 1974,<ref name=eagles /> part of a larger $780,000 restoration of Fort Greene Park.<ref>Lockwood, Charles. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/06/10/90444396.pdf \"Restoration of Fort Greene Park to Begin\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 10, 1973). Accessed: January 17, 2012</ref> They were again removed in 1981 and two of them are on display at the Central Park [[Arsenal (Central Park)|Arsenal]], the administrative headquarters of the New York City Parks Department.<ref name=parks /> They presently flank the third floor entrance.<ref>[http://www.nycgovparks.org/about/history/the-arsenal \"The Arsenal\"] on the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] website</ref>\n\nIn 1995, an examination of the vault reported it held bone fragments in 20 slate boxes, each {{convert|2|by|2|by|7|ft|spell=in}}.<ref name=nyt1995>Martin, Douglas. [https://www.nytimes.com/1995/09/23/nyregion/resurrecting-patriots-their-park-shrine-revolution-s-martyrs-part-fort-greene.html \"Resurrecting Patriots, and Their Park; Shrine to Revolution's Martyrs Is Part of Fort Greene Renewal\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (September 23, 1995). Accessed January 17, 2012</ref> During the park system's inspection in 1995, graffiti was noted to be on the crypt's interior walls. The graffiti is questionably dated to go back to 1973, 1908, and as one tag was scribbled, 1776 \u2014 which is anachronistic considering that this was before the tomb was even built, in 1908.<ref name=nyt1995/>\n\nDuring a site review on January 7, 2000, Park System workers raised the lid of the stone coffin of Benjamin Romaine. The interior of the coffin appeared to have contained a partially collapsed wooden coffin.<ref name=\"homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com\"/> By then, the monument was missing plaques, the plaza was potholed,<ref name=\"articles.nydailynews.com\"/> the crypt had a plywood door, and the eternal flame had long been extinguished.\n\n====Archaeological excavation of original site====\nIn December 2003, a dig was done on the original site of the Martyrs' Monument. The site dig was funded by a grant of $2,500 from the J. M. Kaplan Fund.<ref>O'Grady, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/13/nyregion/what-remains-day-vinegar-hill-last-look-revolutionary-war-grave-site.html \"What Remains of the Day; In Vinegar Hill, a Last Look at a Revolutionary War Grave Site\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (December 13, 2003)</ref> It was supervised by Dr. Joan H. Geismar an archaeological consultant. The original site (block 44, lot 14 Brooklyn) is located on 89 Hudson Ave (formerly Jackson Street: named after an early donor of the property for the Monument in 1808).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maps.google.com?q=&hl=en&ll=40.701973,-73.98119&spn=0.000351,0.000525&sll=40.716823,-73.942872&sspn=0.000353,0.000525&t=h&gl=us&hnear=87+Hudson+Avenue,+Brooklyn,+NY+11201&z=21&layer=c&cbll=40.701973,-73.98119&panoid=-r2l2fUZrUz1R5gNXKivaQ&cbp=12,93.9,,0,12.63|title=Google Maps|work=google.com}}</ref> The goals of the dig were to review if any more human remains could be found on the site and if evidence of the original crypt remained. The site was scheduled for housing development to begin on the site. The Crypt location was specifically identified from an 1855 [[Sanborn Maps|Perris insurance atlas]] as well as a mid-19th-century manuscript map found in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]]. The work determined that the site at one time contained a deep void, but no foundations were found. They did find a massive stone side wall as well as the likely original post holes for the rail fence. The site development was allowed with a recommendation of a plaque when work was done.<ref name=nyt1 /> The redevelopment of the site was completed and eventually the property changed owners. The status of the plaque is not known and currently there is no plaque on the site.\n\n====Renovation and re-dedication ceremony====\nThe city launched the renovation of the Prison Ship Monument with a $3.5 million budget in 2004.<ref name=capital /> The scheduled repairs were plagued by cost overruns and the initial electrical contractor was fired by New York City and needed to be replaced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nygoe.wordpress.com/2008/08/24/aar-prison-ship-martyrs-monument-82308/|title=AAR Prison Ship Martyrs Monument 8/23/08|work=Gathering of Eagles: NY}}</ref> Additionally, a new spiral staircase was built inside the memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/new-york/renovation-of-prison-ship-martyrs-memorial-will/14366/|title=Renovation of Prison Ship Martyrs Memorial Will Light Up Fort Greene Park|publisher=}}</ref> A budgetary study was conducted from March 6, 2006 to September 5, 2008 on electrical improvements and the cost estimated to about $341,000.\n\nThe restored monument was unveiled on November 15, 2008, a centennial celebration, at a rededication ceremony commissioned by the Fort Greene Park Conservancy to celebrate the centennial and re-dedication of the Fort Greene Park Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument. More than 500 people gathered to take part in the relighting of the flame to mark the 100th anniversary.<ref name=\"brooklynpaper.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/32/46/32_46_wy_fg_monument_lights.html|title=It's lights out at Prison Ships memorial|work=The Brooklyn Paper}}</ref> That night, the column and urn were lit by a spectacular lighting scheme.<ref name=parkres>{{cite web|title=Restored Prison Ship Martyrs Monument At Fort Greene Unveiled On Its Centennial Celebration|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/pressrelease/20782|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|date=November 15, 2008}}</ref> The overall restoration cost for the monument from 2006 to 2008 was an estimated $5,100,000.<ref name=capital /> However, in November 2009, it was noted that the light was again not working. The parks department worked to restore the lights and noted that although the lights were working correctly, there was a programming issue with the light timer.<ref name=\"brooklynpaper.com\"/>\n\n===={{Anchor|Edward Snowden statue}} Snowden statue incident====\n{{Main|Statue of Edward Snowden}}\nIn April 2015, a group of anonymous vandals [[guerilla art|illicitly installed]] a 100-pound [[statue of Edward Snowden]], the [[National Security Agency]] whistle blower, atop one of the four columns at the edge of the memorial. It was removed the same day by Parks Department personnel.<ref>[[Associated Press]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/04/06/us/ap-us-snowden-statue-mystery.html \"Bust of Edward Snowden Sneaked Into, Removed From NYC Park\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'' (April 6, 2015)</ref>\n\n===Description===\n[[File:Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument plaque.jpg|thumb|right|237px|The plaque at the base of the monument]]\n[[File:Adolph Weinman eagle.JPG|right|thumb|237px|One of the four [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]] eagles that stood at the base of the large column until 1966]]\n\n====Details====\n* '''The column:''' Constructed of granite, its single [[Doric column]] {{convert|149|ft|m}} in height sits over the crypt at the top of a {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} staircase with 99 steps. When it was built, it was the world's tallest Doric column.<ref name=hinds /> The column carries the inscription: \"1776 THE PRISON SHIP MARTYRS MONUMENT 1908\". The monument's column contained a staircase accessed by a bronze door.<ref name=catalogue /> The stone for the monument came from Lacasse quarry, about {{convert|4|mi|spell=in}} east of [[Newport (city), Vermont|Newport, Vermont]].<ref>Dale, T. Nelson. [http://pubs.usgs.gov/bul/0738/report.pdf ''The Commercial Granites of New England''] Washington D.C: [[United States Department of the Interior]]/[[United States Geological Survey]], 1923. p. 120.</ref> The grand staircase of 100 {{convert|80|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} granite steps rises in three stages. At the foot of the staircase, the entrance to the vault was covered by a slab of brown sandstone, now in storage,<ref name=parks /> that bears the names of the 1808 monument committee and builders, as well as this inscription:<ref name=catalogue>New York Art Commission, [https://books.google.com/books?id=b9cNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA27& ''Catalogue of the Works of Art Belonging to the City of New York''] (1920), Vol. II, pp. 27\u20138. Accessed: January 17, 2012</ref>\n\n{{quote|In the name of the spirits of<br />the departed free<br />sacred to the memory of that por-<br />tion of American seamen, soldiers &<br />citizens who perished in the cause of<br />liberty & their country on board the<br />prison ships of the British (during the<br />Revolutionary War) at the Wall-about.<br />This is the corner stone of the vault<br />which contains their relics. Erected by<br />the Tammany Society or Columbian<br />Order of the City of New York. The ground<br />for which was bestowed by John Jackson<br />Nassau Island, season of blossoms<br />year of discovery, the 316th<br />of the institution the 19th and of<br />American Independence the 32nd<br />April the 6th, 1808.|style=text-align:center}}\n* '''Urn:''' At the top of the column are uprights {{convert|2|ft|spell=in}} in diameter which are the shape of lion's heads. Each head weighs more than {{convert|100|lb}}. These hold up the urn.<ref>{{cite book|title=Architects' and Builders' Magazine|date=1909|publisher=William T. Comstock|page=146|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GFI2AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA146}}</ref> At the top of the column is an eight-ton bronze [[brazier]] or a [[funeral urn]].<ref name=parks/> The urn, which is {{convert|22.5|ft}} tall and weighs 7.5 tons, was cast by the Whale Creek Iron Works in Greepoint from designs of Manhattan sculptor [[Adolph Alexander Weinman]].<ref>\"Fort Greene Historic District Designation Report\", p. 11.</ref> The top of the urn is glazed with extra heavy plate glass. The inside of the urn contains the mechanics for the lighting. The top had a light, the \"[[eternal flame]]\". It went out in 1921 and was never relit until 1997 when a new solar-powered eternal beacon was turned on as part of a ceremony.<ref>Franz, Bill. [http://www.usmm.org/martyrs.html \"Memorial to martyred mariners rededicated\" (excerpts)] ''[[Newark Star-Ledger]]'' (August 26, 1997)</ref> The solar powered beacon or \"eternal flame\", now consists of solar powered lights reflected from a mirror. It is lit daily during the hours of darkness. Around the urn is a bronze railing also cast at Whale Creek Iron Works.\n* '''Eagles:''' Four {{convert|3|ft|m|adj=mid|-high|spell=in}} open-winged {{convert|300|lb|adj=on}} eagles stood at the corners of the {{convert|200|ft|adj=on}} square terrace at the column's base, each on its own {{convert|2|ft|adj=on|spell=in}} pedestal in front of a {{convert|7|ft|adj=on|spell=in}} Doric column. They were designed by [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]], who also designed the six-ton brazier that sits upon the monument's principal column.<ref name=eagles>Gordon, David. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1974/03/10/121831468.pdf \"Fort Greene Park to Get Lost Eagles\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (March 10, 1974). Accessed: January 17, 2012</ref>\n* '''Vault:''' The crypt is in a vault at the base of the stairs. Inside the vault the floor is made of concrete and the walls and ceiling are a bisque-colored brick. One enters the crypt through a copper-clad door. When entering it is three steps down and then a short passageway into the hill and at the end of the passage is the brick-lined crypt. The crypt is approximately {{convert|15|to|20|ft}} square. There are a series of slate coffins inserted into a double-set of shelves on the right and left.<ref name=\"homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com\">[http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~promaine/martyrs/index.html \"Prison Ship Martyrs Monument, Fort Greene, Brooklyn\"] on the RootsWeb website</ref> Various bones are said to be sorted by type into different coffins, presumably because individual bodies could not be identified and re-assembled for burial.<ref name=\"bklyn-genealogy-info.com\"/>\n\n====Monument additions====\nA plaque was added in 1960 located across from the front label on the monument. The plaque reads:<ref name=\"abbyw.com\" />\n\nIn memory of the 11,500 patriotic American sailors and soldiers who endured untold suffering and died on the British prison ships anchored in Wallabout during the Revolutionary War, 1776 - 1782. Their remains lie buried in the crypt at the base of this monument which was dedicated on November 14, 1908. This plaque was affixed by The Society of Old Brooklynites on June 1, 1960. Foelly Crane, M.D. President.\n\nDuring the [[United States Bicentennial|Bicentennial Year]] \u2013 1976, King [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|Juan Carlos]] of Spain dedicated a plaque honoring the 700 Spaniards who died on the prison ships.<ref name=nyt1995 />\n\nCurrently surrounding the monument are secured exhibits explaining the history of the prison ships, the Battle of Brooklyn and a list of the 8,000 known martyrs.<ref name=\"abbyw.com\" /> It is not documented when these exhibits were added.\n\nNear the monument, a small building designed to coordinate with the work of McKim, Mead, and White once provided restroom facilities but was re-purposed as a visitors' center for the park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prison Ship Martyrs Monument|url=http://www.placematters.net/node/1428|publisher=PlaceMatters|accessdate=December 3, 2012}}</ref> The visitors center has pictorial exhibits plus displays of Revolutionary War weapons and uniform buttons that have been uncovered in the park over the years. It also houses a list of the 8,000 known prisoners on the ships copied from the records in the British War Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmm.org/revdead.html|title=American Prisoners of the Revolution Names of 8000 Men Aboard the Old Jersey Prison ship|work=usmm.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=cr&CRid=2227940&CScn=Prison+ship&|title=Find A Grave: Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument at Find a grave lists 301 names|work=findagrave.com}}</ref>\n\n===Current designation and responsibility===\nIn the first half of the 20th century efforts were made to seek a national designation. However, the [[United States Department of the Interior]] declined at the time and noted that the prisoners didn't die at the site itself.<ref name=\"abbyw.com\"/> Currently, the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] is responsible for the preservation and supervision of the monument. A budgetary study was conducted from March 6, 2006, to September 5, 2008, on electrical improvements and the cost estimated at $341,000. The overall restoration cost for the monument from 2006 to 2008 was estimated at $5,100,000.<ref name=capital>[http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/capital \"Fort Greene Park: Capital Projects\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108213326/http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/capital |date=January 8, 2010 }} on the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] website. Accessed January 16, 2012</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2013, U.S. Congressman [[Hakeem Jeffries]] \u2013 representing parts of [[Queens]] and [[Brooklyn]], including [[Fort Greene, Brooklyn|Fort Greene]] \u2013 introduced the \"[[Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument Preservation Act (H.R. 1501; 113th Congress)|Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument Preservation Act]]\" to the [[United States House of Representatives]]. The bill directs the [[United States Department of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] to study the suitability and feasibility of designating the Prison Ship Martyr's Monument as a unit of the [[National Park System]].<ref name=1501sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1501 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1501|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> The study would look at what it would cost to run the park and how its proposed designation as a National Park would affect the surrounding area.<ref name=gop1501>{{cite web|last=Leviner|first=Emily|title=Legislative Digest on H.R. 1501|url=https://www.gop.gov/bill/h-r-1501-prison-ship-martyrs-monument-preservation-act/|publisher=House Republicans|accessdate=May 1, 2014|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The House voted on April 28, 2014 to pass the bill in a [[voice vote]].<ref name=1501allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1501 \u2013 All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1501/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>  The legislation would authorize a $150,000 study to determine if turning the memorial into a national monument would be feasible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/prison-ship-martyrs-bill-passes-house-article-1.1773264#ixzz3BX7OkaqV|title=Prison Ship Martyrs bill passes House|work=NY Daily News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Prisoners in the American Revolutionary War]]\n* [[British Prison Hulks]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* Cray, Robert E., Jr.. \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead: Revolutionary Memory and the Politics of Sepulture in the Early Republic, 1776\u20131808,\" Third series, vol. 56, no. 3, (July 1999)\n* [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]. [http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/FortGreene_DR.pdf \"Fort Greene Historic District Designation Report\"] (September 26, 1978)\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument}}\n* [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1908-11-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1836&index=1&rows=20&words=Jersey+JERSEY+prison+PRISON+Ship+SHIP&searchType=basic&sequence=0&state=&date2=1922&proxtext=Jersey+Prison+Ship&y=11&x=16&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 ''New York Tribune'' of November 11, 1908 having engravings of the 1839 and 1867 tomb memorials]\n* [http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/ Prison Ship Martyrs Association] website\n* [http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=13222 Historical Marker Database: Prison Ship Martyrs Monument], additional images\n* [http://www.mindfulwalker.com/explore-new-york/in-our-midst-the-prison-ship-martyrs Mindful Walker: \"In Our Midst: The Prison Ship Martyrs,\" September 30, 2010], additional images\n* [http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/ Prison Ship Martyrs Association], including [http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/monument.html additional images]\n* [http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~promaine/martyrs/martyrs-all.html Photo gallery]\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2227940/Prison-Ship-Martyrs'-Monument Prison Ship Monument memorials Find a grave website]\n\n{{New York in the American Revolutionary War|state=collapsed}}\n{{Adolph Weinman}}\n{{Public art in Brooklyn}}\n\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War prisoners of war held by Great Britain]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War sites]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Vandalized works of art in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Monumental columns in the United States]]\n[[Category:Military monuments and memorials in the United States]]\n[[Category:New York (state) in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Martyrs' monuments and memorials]]\n[[Category:1908 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1908]]\n[[Category:Stone sculptures in New York City]]\n[[Category:Fort Greene, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of birds in the United States]]\n[[Category:Works by Adolph Weinman]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Monument in Brooklyn, New York}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Coord|40.6918|N|73.9756|W|display=title}}\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1    = Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument from southwest.jpg\n| width1    = 211\n| caption1  = Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument (2013)\n| image2    = Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument top from southwest.jpg\n| width2    = 206\n| caption2  = [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]]'s brazier at the top\n}}\n[[File:Program of the Dedicatory Ceremonies of the Prison Ship Martyrs Monument (1908).jpg|thumb|225px|Program for the dedication ceremonies, November 14, 1908]]\n\nThe '''Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument''' in [[Fort Greene Park]], in the [[New York City]] [[borough (New York City)|borough]] of [[Brooklyn]], is a memorial to the more than 11,500 American [[prisoners of war]] who died in captivity aboard sixteen British [[prison ship]]s during the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref name=nyt1995 /> The remains of a small fraction of those who died on the ships are interred in a [[crypt]] beneath its base. The ships included [[HMS Jersey (1736)|HMS ''Jersey'']], ''Scorpion'', ''Hope'', ''Falmouth'', ''Stromboli'', ''Hunter'', and others.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 568\u20139.</ref><ref name=wilson89>Wilson, James Grant. [https://books.google.com/books?id=KFUOAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA8& ''The memorial History of the City of New-York, From its First Settlement to the Year 1892''], vol. IV New York:New-York History Company, 1893, pp. 8\u20139. Accessed: January 22, 2012</ref>\n\nTheir remains were first gathered and interred in 1808. In 1867 landscape architects [[Frederick Law Olmsted]] and [[Calvert Vaux]], designers of [[Central Park]] and [[Prospect Park (Brooklyn)|Prospect Park]], were engaged to prepare a new design for Washington Park as well as a new crypt for the remains of the prison ship martyrs.<ref name=parks>[http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/monuments/1222 \"Fort Greene Park: Prison Ship Martyrs Monument: History\"] on the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] website</ref> In 1873, after development near the [[Brooklyn Navy Yard]] uncovered the remains, they were moved and re-interred in a crypt beneath a small monument. Funds were raised for a larger monument, which was designed by noted architect [[Stanford White]]. Constructed of granite, its single Doric column {{convert|149|ft|m}} in height sits over the crypt at the top of a {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} 33-step staircase. At the top of the column is an eight-ton bronze [[brazier]], a funeral urn, by sculptor [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]]. President-elect [[William Howard Taft]] delivered the principal address when the monument was dedicated in 1908.\n\n==Context==\n\n===Remains of deceased prisoners===\n{{main|Prisoners in the American Revolutionary War}}\n\nDuring the Revolutionary War, the British maintained a series of prison ships in New York Harbor and jails on shore for prisoners of war.<ref>Andros, Thomas.  \"The old Jersey captive: Or, A narrative of the captivity of Thomas Andros ... on board the old Jersey prison ship at New York, 1781. In a series of letters to a friend.\" W. Peirce. 1833.</ref><ref>Lang, Patrick J..  \"The horrors of the English prison ships, 1776 to 1783, and the barbarous treatment of the American patriots imprisoned on them.\" Society of the Friendly Sons of Saint Patrick, 1939.</ref> Due to brutal conditions, more Americans died in British jails<ref>{{cite news |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030193/1903-12-07/ed-1/seq-6/#date1=1836&sort=relevance&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&index=6&words=skelatons&proxdistance=5&date2=1922&ortext=&proxtext=skelaton&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=2 |page=2 |newspaper=[[New York Tribune]] |title=Skeletons Found in City Hall Park |date=December 7, 1903 |quote=On December 7, 1903 workman found the remains of two men at the site of the Old hall of Records at City Hall Park in New York City; it had been used as a prison during the American Revolution.}}</ref> and prison ships in [[New York Harbor]] than in all the battles of the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Banks |first1=James Lenox |title=Prison ships in the Revolution: New facts in regard to their management |year=1903}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTimes-18520115\">{{cite news |last1=Hanford |first1=William H. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1852/11/16/75121675.pdf |title=Incidents of the Revolution: Recollections of the Old Sugar House Prison |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=January 15, 1852 |accessdate=February 11, 2011}}</ref>  The British disposed of the bodies of the dead from the jails and ships by quick interment or throwing the bodies overboard. Following the end of the war in 1783, the remains of those who died on the prison ships<ref name=\"abbyw.com\">McDonnell, Sharon. [http://www.abbyw.com/fortgreenepark.org/pages/ASP_0307_PrisonShips.pdf \"Revolutionary Martyrs\"] ''American Spirit'' (March/April 2007)</ref> were neglected, left to lie along the Brooklyn shore on [[Wallabout Bay]], a rural area little visited by New Yorkers.<ref>Cray,  \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", p. 573.</ref> On January 21, 1877,  the ''New York Times'' reported that the dead came from all parts of the nation and \"every state of the Union was represented among them.\"<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1877/01/21/80361957.pdf \"The Prison-Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (January 21, 1877)</ref>\n\nOfficials of the local [[Dutch Reformed Church]] met with resistance from the property owner when they sought to remove the bones to their churchyard.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", p. 574.</ref> Nathaniel Scudder Prime reported on \"skulls and feet, arms and legs sticking out of the crumbling bank in the wildest disorder\".<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Long Island: From Its First Settlement by Europeans to the Year 1845 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=elEOAAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Edwin G. Burrows described the skulls on the coast \"as thick as pumpkins in an autumn cornfield\".<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Edwin G. Burrows|last=Burrows|first=Edwin G.|title=Forgotten Patriots: The Untold Story of American Prisoners During the Revolutionary War|year=2008|publisher=Basic Books|location=New York|isbn=0786727047}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Giddens|first=Elizabeth|title=Memorials and the Forgotten|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/04/nyregion/when-memorials-outlast-the-sentiment-behind-them.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|accessdate=February 10, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 2, 2011}}</ref> During construction at the Naval Yards, workers were not sure what to do with the bones, and they started to fill casks and boxes. They were reburied on the grounds of the nearby John Jackson estate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmm.org/martyrs.html|title=Memorial to martyred mariners rededicated|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nEventually, \"near twenty [[hogsheads]] full of bones were collected by the indefatigable industry of John Jackson, esq. the committee of Tammany Society, and other citizens, to be interred in the vault.\"<ref name=dewitt>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UVBAAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85&dq=Wallabout+Committee+monument&ved=0CFMQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage |page=85 |title=An Historical Account of the Interment of the Remains of the American Martyrs at the Wallabout |first=Benjamin|last=De Witt |year=1808 |publisher=Frank, White, and Co. |accessdate=January 13, 2013 }}</ref> The monument's dedication plaque estimates that 11,500 prisoners of war died in the prison ships, but others estimate the number to be as high as 18,000.<ref>{{cite journal |authorlink=Edwin G. Burrows |last=Burrows |first=Edwin G. |url=https://lihj.cc.stonybrook.edu/2012/articles/the-prisoners-of-new-york/ |title=The Prisoners of New York |journal=Long Island History Journal |year=2011 |volume=22 |number=2}}</ref>\n\n===Political resolve===\nThe movement to commemorate the dead only took off when political differences between Federalists and [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republicans]] deepened in the last years of the eighteenth century and the latter took up the question of a memorial in response to the Federalist erection of a statue of George Washington in 1803.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 575\u20138.</ref> The [[Tammany Society]], headed by Benjamin Romaine<ref>[http://www.nysoclib.org/ledger/people/romaine_benjamin.html \"Benjamin Romaine\"] on the New York Society Library website</ref><ref>[http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~promaine/martyrs/Monument-timeline.html \"Timeline of the Burial of the Prison Ship Martyrs and Benjamin Romaine\"] on the RootsWeb website</ref> was created and grew into a Republican organization. On February 10, 1803 Republican Congressman [[Samuel L. Mitchill]] asked the federal government to erect a monument to the fallen, but had no success<ref name=dewitt /><ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 578\u20139.</ref> They then turned their efforts to a grand ceremonial re-interment of the prisoners' remains, emphasizing less the construction of a monument than something more suited to the common man. Tammany formed the Wallabout Committee in January 1808. Their efforts took strength from renewed anti-British feeling stemming from [[Embargo Act of 1807|British incidents]] in 1806 and 1807. Finally, when President Thomas Jefferson enacted the [[Embargo Act]] of 1808, Tammany and the Republicans used their plans for a re-interment as part of their campaign to bolster anti-British sentiment.\n\n==Precursor vaults and monuments==\n\n===First vault and monument===\nOn April 13, 1808, there was a ceremony to lay the cornerstone of a planned vault. A grand ceremony of re-interment followed on May 26, 1808.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", pp. 584\u20135.</ref> The state voted to provide the Tammany Society $1,000 to build a monument. The Society pocketed the money and the monument was never built.<ref>{{cite book|last=Allen|first=Oliver E.|title=The Tiger: The Rise and Fall of Tammany Hall|date=1993|publisher=Addison-Wesley Publishing Company|p=[https://archive.org/details/tigerrisefalloft00alle/page/21 21]|isbn=0-201-62463-X|url=https://archive.org/details/tigerrisefalloft00alle/page/21|url-access=registration}}</ref> A small square building stood above the 1808 vault with an eagle mounted at the point of the roof.  It was located on a triangular plot of land near the Brooklyn Navy Yard waterfront (Wallabout Bay) in what is now called [[Vinegar Hill, Brooklyn|Vinegar Hill]].<ref name=\"fort-greene.com\">[http://fort-greene.com/monument.html \"The Prison Ship Martyrs Monument\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130903225606/http://fort-greene.com/monument.html |date=September 3, 2013 }} on the Fort Greene Park Conservancy website</ref> A wooden fence with thirteen posts and bars painted with the names of the original thirteen states was erected in front. At the entrance through the fence, an inscription said: \"Portal to the tomb of 11,500 patriot prisoners, who died in dungeons and prison-ships, in and about the City of New-York, during the Revolution.\"<ref>McCulloch, J. R. [https://books.google.com/books?id=U3IrAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA474& ''A Dictionary, Geographical, Statistical, and Historical of the Countries, Places, and Principal Natural Objects in the World'']. New York: Harper & Brothers, 1852, vol. 1, p. 474. Accessed January 17, 2012</ref> The remains were put in long coffins made of bluestone. Extra space was provided in case more bones were discovered during continuing renovations in the Brooklyn Navy Yard.<ref name=hinds>{{cite news|last=Hinds|first=Kate|title=Fort Greene Park's Prison Ships Martyrs Monument|url=http://www.wnyc.org/articles/wnyc-news/2010/may/31/fort-greene-parks-prison-ships-martyrs-monument/|accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=WNYC|date=May 31, 2010}}</ref> Little was done to repair or maintain the vault and eventually the original monument was in a state of disrepair and neglect.<ref name=\"fort-greene.com\"/> In 1839, Benjamin Romaine purchased the land where the Martyrs were buried, in a tax sale from [[Henry Reed Stiles]] for $291.08.<ref name=nyt1>{{cite web|url=http://nytelecom.vo.llnwd.net/o15/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/172.pdf |title=Martyr's Monument/Monument Lot Memo Report on Archeological Investigations |date=December 19, 2003 |accessdate=January 13, 2013 |page=1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131230232257/http://nytelecom.vo.llnwd.net/o15/agencies/lpc/arch_reports/172.pdf |archivedate=December 30, 2013 }}</ref> Later that year on July 4, 1839, Benjamin Romaine made an appeal for support (governmental or civic) to build a monument. In this appeal, Romaine talked about the monument and his intention to use his Revolutionary War pension for the monument.<ref>Childs, C.C. & Childs, E., Jr. \"The tomb of the martyrs\". ''Benjamin Romaine's Review'' (July 4, 1839)</ref> On January 31, 1844, Benjamin Romaine died and was also interred in the crypt as he had been a prisoner of war on the ships.\n\n[[File:Fgpark.jpg|thumb|350px|The new monument in Washington Park, Brooklyn]]\n\n===Second vault and monument===\nLater in the nineteenth century, the idea of erecting of a monument on the vault site attracted only occasional interest until 1873 when an appropriation of $6,500<ref name=\"bklyn-genealogy-info.com\">[http://bklyn-genealogy-info.stevemorse.org/Cemetery/old/1873.revol.html \"Revolutionary Martyrs\"] ''[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]]'' (January 18, 1873) and (January 8, 1888)</ref> was established for a new mausoleum. The new {{convert|25|by|11|ft|adj=on}} brick mausoleum in Fort Greene Park, then known as Washington Park, was constructed.<ref name=wilson89 /><ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead\", p. 588.</ref> The new mausoleum was constructed of Portland granite embellished with pillars and fret work of polished Aberdeen stone. The front of the tomb had the following inscription: \"SACRED TO THE MEMORY, OF OUR SAILORS, SOLDIERS AND CITIZENS, WHO SUFFERED AND DIED ON BOARD BRITISH PRISON SHIPS IN THE WALLABOUT DURING THE AMERICAN REVOLUTION\".<ref name=\"bklyn-genealogy-info.com\"/> On June 18, 1873, the first tomb was emptied of bones and they were moved to this tomb.<ref name=nyt1/> The bones remained here until interest was again built and a new monument could be constructed.\n\n==Third monument==\n\n===History===\n\n====Planning and construction====\nThe Fort Greene Chapter of the DAR was formed in 1896 in Brooklyn to foster the construction of a \"suitable memorial to the memory of martyrs, civilian, military and naval, who perished in the noisome prison ships anchored in the Wallabout Bay during the Revolutionary War\". The group quickly partnered with the Old Brooklynites to increase focus on the memorial.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.abbyw.com/fortgreenepark.org/pages/ASP_0307_PrisonShips.pdf |title=Revolutionary Martyrs |first1=Sharon |last1=McDonnell |publisher=Fort Greene Park |format=[[PDF]] |accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the discovery of additional bones in the Brooklyn Naval Yard in 1899, interest in establishing a significant monument was again renewed.<ref>\"Fort Greene Historic District Designation Report\"</ref><ref>C.B.B. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1903/05/24/102001740.pdf \"The Prison Ship Martyrs\" (letter to the editor)] ''[[New York Times]]'' (May 23, 1903)</ref> On June 16, 1900, the bones found during additional excavations in the Brooklyn Navy Yard were interred in the crypt with full military honors. The boxes were reported to be oak, {{convert|5|ft|spell=in}} long and {{convert|2|ft|spell=in}} wide.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1900/06/17/102600886.pdf \"Prison Ship Martyrs Buried in Fort Greene] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 17, 1900)</ref> On June 19, 1900, the Brooklyn Eagle reported that a committee had been appointed to build a larger memorial to replace the current one. Due to the work of this committee, funds for a new monument were finally considered and raised.\n\nFunding for a larger monument came from all levels of government. On June 28, 1902, a joint resolution of the House and Senate appropriated $100,000 for the memorial construction under the provision that an additional $100,000 be raised from other sources.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1902/06/28/101274900.pdf \"For Monument toPrison Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 28, 1902)</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1902/06/17/101955518.pdf \"To Prison Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 17, 1902)</ref> In the following months, New York State provided $25,000, and New York City $50,000, while private contributions provided another $25,000.<ref>Cray, \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead,\" 589</ref><ref>\"Gleanings from American Art Centers,\" ''Brush and Pencil'', vol. 12, no. 4 (July 1903), 291\u20132</ref> Following funds being established, the Prison Ship Martyrs Association was incorporated in Albany on May 9, 1903<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1903/05/10/105052692.pdf \"For Prison Ship Martyrs\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (May 10, 1903)</ref> to oversee the work and the renowned architect [[Stanford White]] (1853\u20131906) of the architectural firm of [[McKim, Mead & White]] was commissioned to design it. The contract for construction of the monument was awarded to Carlin Construction Company under the project supervision of Lieut. Col. [[William Louis Marshall|W. L. Marshall]].<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1907/03/12/106743624.pdf \"Monument Contract Let. Carlin Construction Company to Build Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (March 12, 1907)</ref>\nIn 1776, Fort Greene Park was the site of [[Fort Putnam]], one of a series of defenses built on the high land in Brooklyn. The construction was supervised by Colonel [[Rufus Putnam]] and the purpose was to protect New York from the British.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n====Dedication ceremony====\nThe dedication ceremony on November 15, 1908, included a parade with 15,000 participants, including military and National Guard units, veterans, and civic organizations, including representatives of [[Tammany Hall|Tammany Hall Society]] in their first parade since the Civil War. President-elect [[William Howard Taft]], Secretary of War [[Luke Edward Wright|Luke E. Wright]], New York Governor [[Charles Evans Hughes]], New Jersey Governor [[John Franklin Fort|Franklin Fort]], and Delaware Governor [[Preston Lea]] watched along with approximately twenty thousand spectators as \"the enormous flag draping the Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument on the highest point of Fort Greene Park, Brooklyn, was allowed to slide slowly to the ground from its heighth {{sic}} of 198 feet in the air\".<ref name=taft-and-hughes /> The ceremony was opened with a prayer delivered by Rev. [[S. Parkes Cadman]], followed by a poem composed and read by the occasion's poet laureate [[Thomas Walsh (poet)|Thomas Walsh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nation Honors Martyred Dead|url=http://bklyn.newspapers.com/image/53948216|accessdate=December 23, 2016|work=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=November 15, 1908|page=6|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The principal address was delivered by Taft.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1908/11/14/104768987.pdf |title=Martyrs' Monument Day in Brooklyn |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=November 14, 1908 |accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref> He set out in detail the treatment of American prisoners and of the dead he said: \"They died because of the cruelty of their immediate custodians and the neglect of those who, in higher authority, were responsible for their detention.\"<ref name=\"taft-and-hughes\" /> He carefully described British culpability:\n\n{{quote|I do not wish to be understood as charging that these conditions were due to the premeditations of the English commanders in chief or to the set purposes of anyone in authority having to do with the fate of the unfortunate men whose bravery and self-sacrifice this monument records. Such a charge would make the British commanders human monsters. The conditions were the result of neglect, not design.}}\n\nHe discussed the treatment of prisoners of war throughout history and praised the recent [[Hague Conventions of 1899 and 1907|Hague Convention]] on the rights of prisoners of war and the recent [[First Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]] in which \"both parties exceeded, in the tenderness and the care which they gave to the prisoners of the other, the requirements of the Hague Convention\".<ref name=taft-and-hughes>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1908/11/15/104812779.pdf |title=Taft and Hughes at Martyrs' Shaft |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=November 15, 1908 |accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the initial dedication, the Society of Old Brooklynites has hosted an annual memorial for the martyrs every year since President Taft dedicated the monument in 1908.<ref name=nyt1995/>\n\n====Repeated neglect and restoration====\nIn February 1914, one of the eagles was stolen. The thieves attempted to sell it as scrap metal for $24.<ref name=stolen>{{cite news|title=Huge Bronze Eagle Stolen from Park|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1914/02/02/101430037.pdf |accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=February 2, 1914}}</ref> The thieves broke the eagle from the granite base, rolled it down the slope and loaded it on a three-wheeled push cart, leaving tracks which the police were able to follow. When police found it at a recycling yard, the wings of the eagle had already been removed and partially melted.<ref name=stolen/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CRMbAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA176&lpg=PA176&dq=Prison+Ship+Martyrs%27+Monument&source=bl&ots=f7DHKyPbb7&sig=JoMlNfx88X6YQDBGDsdqvQkS_V0&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6d_9U-K4EJO6ogSN1oBI&ved=0CFQQ6AEwCThG#v=onepage&q=Prison%20Ship%20Martyrs'%20Monument&f=false|title=Documents of the Assembly of the State of New York|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Eagle by Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument.jpg|left|thumb|One of four bronze eagles by Adolph Weinman at the restored monument site.]]\n\nBy 1921, the beacon was out. The twin helix stairways to the top of the monument, which visitors once paid a dime to climb,<ref name=\"articles.nydailynews.com\">[http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-11-15/news/17910101_1_freedom-fighters-new-yorker-forgotten-patriots \"Memorial to Revolutionary War patriots shines anew in Brooklyn\"] ''[[New York Daily News]]'' (November 14, 2008)</ref> were closed. Until then, visitors could go to the top to get impressive views of Manhattan. In 1923, the bronze door to the crypt was \"battered from its hinges\" by vandals and the crypt was exposed. The ''[[New York Times]]'' report of the incident described how the monument provided a play area for neighborhood children: \"[A] score of children, white and black, who live in the neighborhood were using the granite coping of the walls leading to the crypt as a sort of 'chute the chutes.' The color line was sharply drawn. The slope of one side was used by the negro children while the slope of the other side amused the whites. The children of neither hue were concerned with the crime. They realized vaguely that something unusual had taken place, but it was not important enough to them to stop their daily sport.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Smash Bronze Door to Martyrs' Tomb|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1923/05/12/105994187.pdf |accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 12, 1923}}</ref> However, neglect and damage to the park required it to be renovated. The memorial had become so scarred by vandals and unkempt from lack of proper maintenance as to present a dilapidated appearance. Work was done to clean and preserve the site. A staircase and elevator were installed inside the large column, and it was reopened in 1937 by Park Commissioner [[Robert Moses]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Historic Fort Greene Park is Reopened; Ceremony Marks Restoration of Area|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1937/06/30/94394948.pdf|accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 30, 1937}}</ref> Again, the park was neglected and restoration work was required. It began in 1948 to \"keep the shrine from falling apart\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Shaft of Martyrs Saved in Brooklyn|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1949/07/10/84273243.pdf|accessdate=December 3, 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=July 10, 1949}}</ref> The staircase and elevator, however, were both removed in 1949.<ref name=nyt1995 /><ref name=parks /> In 1966, the eagles were removed and went missing until 1974.\n\nIn the ensuing years, however, the park slowly decayed again and, by the 1970s, graffiti covered much of the base of the monument and vandalism was taking its toll.<ref>[http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/monument.html \"The Monument\"] on the Prison Ship Martyrs Association website</ref> After being vandalized repeatedly, the four eagles were removed for repairs in 1966 and restored when $251,000 was spent to repair the monument about 1974,<ref name=eagles /> part of a larger $780,000 restoration of Fort Greene Park.<ref>Lockwood, Charles. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/06/10/90444396.pdf \"Restoration of Fort Greene Park to Begin\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (June 10, 1973). Accessed: January 17, 2012</ref> They were again removed in 1981 and two of them are on display at the Central Park [[Arsenal (Central Park)|Arsenal]], the administrative headquarters of the New York City Parks Department.<ref name=parks /> They presently flank the third floor entrance.<ref>[http://www.nycgovparks.org/about/history/the-arsenal \"The Arsenal\"] on the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] website</ref>\n\nIn 1995, an examination of the vault reported it held bone fragments in 20 slate boxes, each {{convert|2|by|2|by|7|ft|spell=in}}.<ref name=nyt1995>Martin, Douglas. [https://www.nytimes.com/1995/09/23/nyregion/resurrecting-patriots-their-park-shrine-revolution-s-martyrs-part-fort-greene.html \"Resurrecting Patriots, and Their Park; Shrine to Revolution's Martyrs Is Part of Fort Greene Renewal\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (September 23, 1995). Accessed January 17, 2012</ref> During the park system's inspection in 1995, graffiti was noted to be on the crypt's interior walls. The graffiti is questionably dated to go back to 1973, 1908, and as one tag was scribbled, 1776 \u2014 which is anachronistic considering that this was before the tomb was even built, in 1908.<ref name=nyt1995/>\n\nDuring a site review on January 7, 2000, Park System workers raised the lid of the stone coffin of Benjamin Romaine. The interior of the coffin appeared to have contained a partially collapsed wooden coffin.<ref name=\"homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com\"/> By then, the monument was missing plaques, the plaza was potholed,<ref name=\"articles.nydailynews.com\"/> the crypt had a plywood door, and the eternal flame had long been extinguished.\n\n====Archaeological excavation of original site====\nIn December 2003, a dig was done on the original site of the Martyrs' Monument. The site dig was funded by a grant of $2,500 from the J. M. Kaplan Fund.<ref>O'Grady, Jim. [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/12/13/nyregion/what-remains-day-vinegar-hill-last-look-revolutionary-war-grave-site.html \"What Remains of the Day; In Vinegar Hill, a Last Look at a Revolutionary War Grave Site\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (December 13, 2003)</ref> It was supervised by Dr. Joan H. Geismar an archaeological consultant. The original site (block 44, lot 14 Brooklyn) is located on 89 Hudson Ave (formerly Jackson Street: named after an early donor of the property for the Monument in 1808).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://maps.google.com?q=&hl=en&ll=40.701973,-73.98119&spn=0.000351,0.000525&sll=40.716823,-73.942872&sspn=0.000353,0.000525&t=h&gl=us&hnear=87+Hudson+Avenue,+Brooklyn,+NY+11201&z=21&layer=c&cbll=40.701973,-73.98119&panoid=-r2l2fUZrUz1R5gNXKivaQ&cbp=12,93.9,,0,12.63|title=Google Maps|work=google.com}}</ref> The goals of the dig were to review if any more human remains could be found on the site and if evidence of the original crypt remained. The site was scheduled for housing development to begin on the site. The Crypt location was specifically identified from an 1855 [[Sanborn Maps|Perris insurance atlas]] as well as a mid-19th-century manuscript map found in the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]]. The work determined that the site at one time contained a deep void, but no foundations were found. They did find a massive stone side wall as well as the likely original post holes for the rail fence. The site development was allowed with a recommendation of a plaque when work was done.<ref name=nyt1 /> The redevelopment of the site was completed and eventually the property changed owners. The status of the plaque is not known and currently there is no plaque on the site.\n\n====Renovation and re-dedication ceremony====\nThe city launched the renovation of the Prison Ship Monument with a $3.5 million budget in 2004.<ref name=capital /> The scheduled repairs were plagued by cost overruns and the initial electrical contractor was fired by New York City and needed to be replaced.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nygoe.wordpress.com/2008/08/24/aar-prison-ship-martyrs-monument-82308/|title=AAR Prison Ship Martyrs Monument 8/23/08|work=Gathering of Eagles: NY}}</ref> Additionally, a new spiral staircase was built inside the memorial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nysun.com/new-york/renovation-of-prison-ship-martyrs-memorial-will/14366/|title=Renovation of Prison Ship Martyrs Memorial Will Light Up Fort Greene Park|publisher=}}</ref> A budgetary study was conducted from March 6, 2006 to September 5, 2008 on electrical improvements and the cost estimated to about $341,000.\n\nThe restored monument was unveiled on November 15, 2008, a centennial celebration, at a rededication ceremony commissioned by the Fort Greene Park Conservancy to celebrate the centennial and re-dedication of the Fort Greene Park Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument. More than 500 people gathered to take part in the relighting of the flame to mark the 100th anniversary.<ref name=\"brooklynpaper.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklynpaper.com/stories/32/46/32_46_wy_fg_monument_lights.html|title=It's lights out at Prison Ships memorial|work=The Brooklyn Paper}}</ref> That night, the column and urn were lit by a spectacular lighting scheme.<ref name=parkres>{{cite web|title=Restored Prison Ship Martyrs Monument At Fort Greene Unveiled On Its Centennial Celebration|url=http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/pressrelease/20782|publisher=[[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]]|date=November 15, 2008}}</ref> The overall restoration cost for the monument from 2006 to 2008 was an estimated $5,100,000.<ref name=capital /> However, in November 2009, it was noted that the light was again not working. The parks department worked to restore the lights and noted that although the lights were working correctly, there was a programming issue with the light timer.<ref name=\"brooklynpaper.com\"/>\n\n===={{Anchor|Edward Snowden statue}} Snowden statue incident====\n{{Main|Statue of Edward Snowden}}\nIn April 2015, a group of anonymous vandals [[guerilla art|illicitly installed]] a 100-pound [[statue of Edward Snowden]], the [[National Security Agency]] whistle blower, atop one of the four columns at the edge of the memorial. It was removed the same day by Parks Department personnel.<ref>[[Associated Press]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/04/06/us/ap-us-snowden-statue-mystery.html \"Bust of Edward Snowden Sneaked Into, Removed From NYC Park\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'' (April 6, 2015)</ref>\n\n===Description===\n[[File:Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument plaque.jpg|thumb|right|237px|The plaque at the base of the monument]]\n[[File:Adolph Weinman eagle.JPG|right|thumb|237px|One of the four [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]] eagles that stood at the base of the large column until 1966]]\n\n====Details====\n* '''The column:''' Constructed of granite, its single [[Doric column]] {{convert|149|ft|m}} in height sits over the crypt at the top of a {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} staircase with 99 steps. When it was built, it was the world's tallest Doric column.<ref name=hinds /> The column carries the inscription: \"1776 THE PRISON SHIP MARTYRS MONUMENT 1908\". The monument's column contained a staircase accessed by a bronze door.<ref name=catalogue /> The stone for the monument came from Lacasse quarry, about {{convert|4|mi|spell=in}} east of [[Newport (city), Vermont|Newport, Vermont]].<ref>Dale, T. Nelson. [http://pubs.usgs.gov/bul/0738/report.pdf ''The Commercial Granites of New England''] Washington D.C: [[United States Department of the Interior]]/[[United States Geological Survey]], 1923. p. 120.</ref> The grand staircase of 100 {{convert|80|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} granite steps rises in three stages. At the foot of the staircase, the entrance to the vault was covered by a slab of brown sandstone, now in storage,<ref name=parks /> that bears the names of the 1808 monument committee and builders, as well as this inscription:<ref name=catalogue>New York Art Commission, [https://books.google.com/books?id=b9cNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA27& ''Catalogue of the Works of Art Belonging to the City of New York''] (1920), Vol. II, pp. 27\u20138. Accessed: January 17, 2012</ref>\n\n{{quote|In the name of the spirits of<br />the departed free<br />sacred to the memory of that por-<br />tion of American seamen, soldiers &<br />citizens who perished in the cause of<br />liberty & their country on board the<br />prison ships of the British (during the<br />Revolutionary War) at the Wall-about.<br />This is the corner stone of the vault<br />which contains their relics. Erected by<br />the Tammany Society or Columbian<br />Order of the City of New York. The ground<br />for which was bestowed by John Jackson<br />Nassau Island, season of blossoms<br />year of discovery, the 316th<br />of the institution the 19th and of<br />American Independence the 32nd<br />April the 6th, 1808.|style=text-align:center}}\n* '''Urn:''' At the top of the column are uprights {{convert|2|ft|spell=in}} in diameter which are the shape of lion's heads. Each head weighs more than {{convert|100|lb}}. These hold up the urn.<ref>{{cite book|title=Architects' and Builders' Magazine|date=1909|publisher=William T. Comstock|page=146|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GFI2AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA146}}</ref> At the top of the column is an eight-ton bronze [[brazier]] or a [[funeral urn]].<ref name=parks/> The urn, which is {{convert|22.5|ft}} tall and weighs 7.5 tons, was cast by the Whale Creek Iron Works in Greepoint from designs of Manhattan sculptor [[Adolph Alexander Weinman]].<ref>\"Fort Greene Historic District Designation Report\", p. 11.</ref> The top of the urn is glazed with extra heavy plate glass. The inside of the urn contains the mechanics for the lighting. The top had a light, the \"[[eternal flame]]\". It went out in 1921 and was never relit until 1997 when a new solar-powered eternal beacon was turned on as part of a ceremony.<ref>Franz, Bill. [http://www.usmm.org/martyrs.html \"Memorial to martyred mariners rededicated\" (excerpts)] ''[[Newark Star-Ledger]]'' (August 26, 1997)</ref> The solar powered beacon or \"eternal flame\", now consists of solar powered lights reflected from a mirror. It is lit daily during the hours of darkness. Around the urn is a bronze railing also cast at Whale Creek Iron Works.\n* '''Eagles:''' Four {{convert|3|ft|m|adj=mid|-high|spell=in}} open-winged {{convert|300|lb|adj=on}} eagles stood at the corners of the {{convert|200|ft|adj=on}} square terrace at the column's base, each on its own {{convert|2|ft|adj=on|spell=in}} pedestal in front of a {{convert|7|ft|adj=on|spell=in}} Doric column. They were designed by [[Adolph Alexander Weinman|Adolf Weinman]], who also designed the six-ton brazier that sits upon the monument's principal column.<ref name=eagles>Gordon, David. [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1974/03/10/121831468.pdf \"Fort Greene Park to Get Lost Eagles\"] ''[[New York Times]]'' (March 10, 1974). Accessed: January 17, 2012</ref>\n* '''Vault:''' The crypt is in a vault at the base of the stairs. Inside the vault the floor is made of concrete and the walls and ceiling are a bisque-colored brick. One enters the crypt through a copper-clad door. When entering it is three steps down and then a short passageway into the hill and at the end of the passage is the brick-lined crypt. The crypt is approximately {{convert|15|to|20|ft}} square. There are a series of slate coffins inserted into a double-set of shelves on the right and left.<ref name=\"homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com\">[http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~promaine/martyrs/index.html \"Prison Ship Martyrs Monument, Fort Greene, Brooklyn\"] on the RootsWeb website</ref> Various bones are said to be sorted by type into different coffins, presumably because individual bodies could not be identified and re-assembled for burial.<ref name=\"bklyn-genealogy-info.com\"/>\n\n====Monument additions====\nA plaque was added in 1960 located across from the front label on the monument. The plaque reads:<ref name=\"abbyw.com\" />\n\nIn memory of the 11,500 patriotic American sailors and soldiers who endured untold suffering and died on the British prison ships anchored in Wallabout during the Revolutionary War, 1776 - 1782. Their remains lie buried in the crypt at the base of this monument which was dedicated on November 14, 1908. This plaque was affixed by The Society of Old Brooklynites on June 1, 1960. Foelly Crane, M.D. President.\n\nDuring the [[United States Bicentennial|Bicentennial Year]] \u2013 1976, King [[Juan Carlos I of Spain|Juan Carlos]] of Spain dedicated a plaque honoring the 700 Spaniards who died on the prison ships.<ref name=nyt1995 />\n\nCurrently surrounding the monument are secured exhibits explaining the history of the prison ships, the Battle of Brooklyn and a list of the 8,000 known martyrs.<ref name=\"abbyw.com\" /> It is not documented when these exhibits were added.\n\nNear the monument, a small building designed to coordinate with the work of McKim, Mead, and White once provided restroom facilities but was re-purposed as a visitors' center for the park.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prison Ship Martyrs Monument|url=http://www.placematters.net/node/1428|publisher=PlaceMatters|accessdate=December 3, 2012}}</ref> The visitors center has pictorial exhibits plus displays of Revolutionary War weapons and uniform buttons that have been uncovered in the park over the years. It also houses a list of the 8,000 known prisoners on the ships copied from the records in the British War Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmm.org/revdead.html|title=American Prisoners of the Revolution Names of 8000 Men Aboard the Old Jersey Prison ship|work=usmm.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=cr&CRid=2227940&CScn=Prison+ship&|title=Find A Grave: Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument at Find a grave lists 301 names|work=findagrave.com}}</ref>\n\n===Current designation and responsibility===\nIn the first half of the 20th century efforts were made to seek a national designation. However, the [[United States Department of the Interior]] declined at the time and noted that the prisoners didn't die at the site itself.<ref name=\"abbyw.com\"/> Currently, the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] is responsible for the preservation and supervision of the monument. A budgetary study was conducted from March 6, 2006, to September 5, 2008, on electrical improvements and the cost estimated at $341,000. The overall restoration cost for the monument from 2006 to 2008 was estimated at $5,100,000.<ref name=capital>[http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/capital \"Fort Greene Park: Capital Projects\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108213326/http://www.nycgovparks.org/parks/FortGreenePark/capital |date=January 8, 2010 }} on the [[New York City Department of Parks and Recreation]] website. Accessed January 16, 2012</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2013, U.S. Congressman [[Hakeem Jeffries]] \u2013 representing parts of [[Queens]] and [[Brooklyn]], including [[Fort Greene, Brooklyn|Fort Greene]] \u2013 introduced the \"[[Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument Preservation Act (H.R. 1501; 113th Congress)|Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument Preservation Act]]\" to the [[United States House of Representatives]]. The bill directs the [[United States Department of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] to study the suitability and feasibility of designating the Prison Ship Martyr's Monument as a unit of the [[National Park System]].<ref name=1501sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1501 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1501|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> The study would look at what it would cost to run the park and how its proposed designation as a National Park would affect the surrounding area.<ref name=gop1501>{{cite web|last=Leviner|first=Emily|title=Legislative Digest on H.R. 1501|url=https://www.gop.gov/bill/h-r-1501-prison-ship-martyrs-monument-preservation-act/|publisher=House Republicans|accessdate=May 1, 2014|date=April 28, 2014}}</ref> The House voted on April 28, 2014 to pass the bill in a [[voice vote]].<ref name=1501allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 1501 \u2013 All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/1501/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>  The legislation would authorize a $150,000 study to determine if turning the memorial into a national monument would be feasible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/prison-ship-martyrs-bill-passes-house-article-1.1773264#ixzz3BX7OkaqV|title=Prison Ship Martyrs bill passes House|work=NY Daily News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Prisoners in the American Revolutionary War]]\n* [[British Prison Hulks]]\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n* Cray, Robert E., Jr.. \"Commemorating the Prison Ship Dead: Revolutionary Memory and the Politics of Sepulture in the Early Republic, 1776\u20131808,\" Third series, vol. 56, no. 3, (July 1999)\n* [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]. [http://www.nyc.gov/html/lpc/downloads/pdf/reports/FortGreene_DR.pdf \"Fort Greene Historic District Designation Report\"] (September 26, 1978)\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Prison Ship Martyrs' Monument}}\n* [http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1908-11-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1836&index=1&rows=20&words=Jersey+JERSEY+prison+PRISON+Ship+SHIP&searchType=basic&sequence=0&state=&date2=1922&proxtext=Jersey+Prison+Ship&y=11&x=16&dateFilterType=yearRange&page=1 ''New York Tribune'' of November 11, 1908 having engravings of the 1839 and 1867 tomb memorials]\n* [http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/ Prison Ship Martyrs Association] website\n* [http://www.hmdb.org/marker.asp?marker=13222 Historical Marker Database: Prison Ship Martyrs Monument], additional images\n* [http://www.mindfulwalker.com/explore-new-york/in-our-midst-the-prison-ship-martyrs Mindful Walker: \"In Our Midst: The Prison Ship Martyrs,\" September 30, 2010], additional images\n* [http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/ Prison Ship Martyrs Association], including [http://www.prisonshipmartyrs.com/monument.html additional images]\n* [http://homepages.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~promaine/martyrs/martyrs-all.html Photo gallery]\n* [https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2227940/Prison-Ship-Martyrs'-Monument Prison Ship Monument memorials Find a grave website]\n\n{{New York in the American Revolutionary War|state=collapsed}}\n{{Adolph Weinman}}\n{{Public art in Brooklyn}}\n\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War prisoners of war held by Great Britain]]\n[[Category:American Revolutionary War sites]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Vandalized works of art in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Monumental columns in the United States]]\n[[Category:Military monuments and memorials in the United States]]\n[[Category:New York (state) in the American Revolution]]\n[[Category:Martyrs' monuments and memorials]]\n[[Category:1908 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1908]]\n[[Category:Stone sculptures in New York City]]\n[[Category:Fort Greene, Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:1908 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of birds in the United States]]\n[[Category:Works by Adolph Weinman]]\n[[Category:Outdoor sculptures in Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user": "Zapeterset", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRepeated neglect and restoration:i was sold according to source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prison_Ship_Martyrs%27_Monument"}
{"title_page": "John St John, 2nd Viscount St John", "text_new": "'''John St John''' (3 May 1702\u20131748) of [[Lydiard Tregoze]], Wiltshire, was a British politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1727 to 1734.\n \nSt John was the second surviving son of  [[Henry St John, 1st Viscount St John]] MP, and his second wife Angelica Magdalena Wharton, widow of Phillip Wharton and daughter of Claude Pelissary, treasurer-general of the navy to Louis XIV.  When John St. John was a child his elder half-brother, Bolingbroke, was attainted and excluded by special remainder from succeeding to the peerage. St John was educated at [[Eton College]] in 1717 and  was sent to Paris in 1720 to complete his education under   Bolingbroke's care. In 1721 his father invested \u00a34,000  to acquire the reversion of a customs sinecure worth \u00a31,200 a year for the lives of his two younger sons, John and Holles. St John  married Anne Furnese, daughter of [[Sir Robert Furnese, 2nd Baronet]]  of [[Waldershare]], Kent on 17 April 1729,<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/st-john-hon-john-1702-48 | title=ST. JOHN, Hon. John (1702-48), of Lydiard Tregoze, Wilts. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 26 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1727 British general election]] after coming of age, St John was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wootton Bassett (UK Parliament constituency)|Wootton Bassett]] on the family interest. He voted with the Opposition except on the repeal of the Septennial Act in 1734. He did not stand again at the [[1734 British general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n[[File:Lydiard House, Swindon.jpg|thumb|250px|Lydiard House from the southwest]]\nSt John was appointed Comptroller of customs in London in April 1740 holding the post for life. On his father's death on 8 April 1742, he succeeded not only to the title under special remainder as 2nd Viscount St. John but to [[Lydiard Park]].  St. John's wife Anne died on 14 July 1747.  St John  married as his second wife Hester Clarke, daughter of James Clarke of Wharton, Herefordshire on 19 June 1748.<ref name=HOP/>\n \nSt. John died abroad in November 1748, leaving  three sons and three daughters.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Robert Murray (1689\u20131738)|Colonel Robert Murray]]\n | before2 = [[William Chetwynd]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wootton Bassett (UK Parliament constituency)|Wootton Bassett]]\n | years =  [[1727 British general election|1727]]\u2013[[1734 British general election|1734]]\n | with  =  [[Sir John Crosse, 2nd Baronet|John Crosse]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Robert Long, 6th Baronet|Sir Robert Long]]\n | after2 = [[Nicholas Robinson (MP)|Captain Nicholas Robinson]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St John, John}}\n[[Category:1702 births]]\n[[Category:1748 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "text_old": "'''John St John''' (3 May 1702\u20131748) of [[Lydiard Tregoze]], Wiltshire, was a British politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] from 1727 to 1734.\n \nSt John was the second surviving son of  [[Henry St John, 1st Viscount St John]] MP, and his second wife Angelica Magdalena Wharton, widow of Phillip Wharton and daughter of Claude Pelissary, treasurer-general of the navy to Louis XIV.  When John St. John was a child his elder half-brother, Bolingbroke, was attainted and excluded by special remainder from succeeding to the peerage. St John was educated at [[Eton College]] in 1717 and  was sent to Paris in 1720 to complete his education under   Bolingbroke\u2019s care. In 1721 his father invested \u00a34,000  to acquire the reversion of a customs sinecure worth \u00a31,200 a year for the lives of his two younger sons, John and Holles. St John  married Anne Furnese, daughter of [[Sir Robert Furnese, 2nd Baronet]]  of [[Waldershare]], Kent on 17 April 1729,<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url =http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/st-john-hon-john-1702-48 | title=ST. JOHN, Hon. John (1702-48), of Lydiard Tregoze, Wilts. | publisher= History of Parliament Online| accessdate = 26 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1727 British general election]] after coming of age, St John was returned as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wootton Bassett (UK Parliament constituency)|Wootton Bassett]] on the family interest. He voted with the Opposition except on the repeal of the Septennial Act in 1734. He did not stand again at the [[1734 British general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n[[File:Lydiard House, Swindon.jpg|thumb|250px|Lydiard House from the southwest]]\nSt John was appointed Comptroller of customs in London in April 1740 holding the post for life. On his father\u2019s death on 8 April 1742, he succeeded not only to the title under special remainder as 2nd Viscount St. John but to [[Lydiard Park]].  St. John\u2019s wife Anne died on 14 July 1747.  St John  married as his second wife Hester Clarke, daughter of James Clarke of Wharton, Herefordshire on 19 June 1748.<ref name=HOP/>\n \nSt. John died abroad in November 1748, leaving  three sons and three daughters.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Robert Murray (1689\u20131738)|Colonel Robert Murray]]\n | before2 = [[William Chetwynd]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Wootton Bassett (UK Parliament constituency)|Wootton Bassett]]\n | years =  [[1727 British general election|1727]]\u2013[[1734 British general election|1734]]\n | with  =  [[Sir John Crosse, 2nd Baronet|John Crosse]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir Robert Long, 6th Baronet|Sir Robert Long]]\n | after2 = [[Nicholas Robinson (MP)|Captain Nicholas Robinson]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St John, John}}\n[[Category:1702 births]]\n[[Category:1748 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_St_John,_2nd_Viscount_St_John"}
{"title_page": "John le Sage", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John Le Sage\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birthname          = John Merry Sage\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1837|4|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]], [[Bristol]], England\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1926|1|1|1837|4|23|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Fulham]], [[London]], England\n| education          = \n| occupation         = Journalist, editor\n| employer           = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| alias              = \n| title              = \n| family             = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Ellen Augusta Kent|1862|1865}}<br />{{marriage|Clara Ellen Scott|1868|1873}}<br/>{{marriage|Elizabeth Lord|1874|1926}}\n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| ethnicity          = \n| religion           = \n| credits            = \n}}\n\n'''John Merry Le Sage''' (23 April 1837 \u2013 1 January 1926), was a British journalist and newspaper editor.\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Clifton, Bristol]], Le Sage was the son of John Sage and his wife Elizabeth, ''n\u00e9e'' Godfrey; Le Sage would adopt the \"Le\" for his last name during middle age. He began his career in journalism when he was employed as a reporter for ''The Torquay Directory and South Devon Journal'', later working for the ''[[Western Morning News]]''. In 1863, he obtained a position with ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' in [[London]], beginning an association with the paper that would last for sixty years.<ref name=\"firth\">J. B. Firth, ''rev''. Joseph Coohill, \"Le Sage, Sir John Merry (1837-1926)\", in ''The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', H.C.G. Matthew and Brian Harrison, eds. (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2004), vol. 33, p. 414.</ref>\n\nLe Sage worked primarily as a foreign correspondent. Though not regarded as a great writer, he was best known for providing the first reports of the [[Siege of Paris (1870-1871)|German troops marching into Paris]] during the [[Franco-Prussian War]] in 1871. He was also present during the period of the [[Paris Commune]], as well as the coronation of [[Alexander III of Russia|Tsar Alexander III]]. He enjoyed a good relationship with first [[Joseph Moses Levy]] and then his son [[Edward Levy-Lawson, 1st Baron Burnham|Edward Levy-Lawson]], successive owners of the ''Daily Telegraph''. When the senior Levy died, Le Sage was named as editor, though Levy-Lawson exercised firm control over the newspaper until he became Baron Burnham in 1903. As editor, Le Sage continued the traditions laid out by his predecessors, focusing on the middle class reader and ignoring criticism of his practices.<ref name=\"firth\" />\n\nThough Le Sage proved a successful editor, by the early 20th century he was having difficulties keeping up with changes in the journalistic profession. Hampered by his age and an unwillingness to delegate responsibility, he nonetheless continued on as editor and was [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom#Knighthood|knighted]] in 1918 in recognition for his services to journalism. Le Sage retired from his post in June 1923 and died on New Year's Day, 1926, at his home in [[Fulham]].<ref>J. B. Firth, ''rev''. Joseph Coohill, \"Le Sage, Sir John Merry (1837-1926)\", in ''The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', H.C.G. Matthew and Brian Harrison, eds. (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2004), vol. 33, pgs. 414-415.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Edwin Arnold]] | title=Editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''| years=1888\u20131923| after=[[Frederick Miller (British journalist)|Frederick Miller]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Le Sage, John Merry}}\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:1837 births]]\n[[Category:1926 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John Le Sage\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birthname          = John Merry Sage\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1837|4|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Clifton, Bristol|Clifton]], [[Bristol]], England\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|1926|1|1|1837|4|23|df=y}}\n| death_place        = [[Fulham]], [[London]], England\n| education          = \n| occupation         = Journalist, editor\n| employer           = ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''\n| alias              = \n| title              = \n| family             = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Ellen Augusta Kent|1862|1865}}<br />{{marriage|Clara Ellen Scott|1868|1873}}<br/>{{marriage|Elizabeth Lord|1874|1926}}\n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| ethnicity          = \n| religion           = \n| credits            = \n}}\n\n'''John Merry Le Sage''' (23 April 1837 \u2013 1 January 1926), was a British journalist and newspaper editor.\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Clifton, Bristol]], Le Sage was the son of John Sage and his wife Elizabeth, ''n\u00e9e'' Godfrey; Le Sage would adopt the \"Le\" for his last name during middle age. He began his career in journalism when he was employed as a reporter for ''The Torquay Directory and South Devon Journal'', later working for the ''[[Western Morning News]]''. In 1863, he obtained a position with ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' in [[London]], beginning an association with the paper that would last for sixty years.<ref name=\"firth\">J. B. Firth, ''rev''. Joseph Coohill, \"Le Sage, Sir John Merry (1837-1926)\", in ''The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', H.C.G. Matthew and Brian Harrison, eds. (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2004), vol. 33, p. 414.</ref>\n\nLe Sage worked primarily as a foreign correspondent. Though not regarded as a great writer, he was best known for providing the first reports of the [[Siege of Paris (1870-1871)|German troops marching into Paris]] during the [[Franco-Prussian War]] in 1871. He was also present during the period of the [[Paris Commune]], as well as the coronation of [[Alexander III of Russia|Tsar Alexander III]]. He enjoyed a good relationship with first [[Joseph Moses Levy]] and then his son [[Edward Levy-Lawson, 1st Baron Burnham|Edward Levy-Lawson]], successive owners of the ''Daily Telegraph''. When the senior Levy died, Le Sage was named as editor, though Levy-Lawson exercised firm control over the newspaper until he became Baron Burnham in 1903. As editor, Le Sage continued the traditions laid out by his predecessors, focusing on the middle class reader and ignoring criticism of his practices.<ref name=\"firth\" />\n\nThough Le Sage proved a successful editor, by the early 20th century he was having difficulties keeping up with changes in the journalistic profession. Hampered by his age and an unwillingness to delegate responsibility, he nonetheless continued on as editor and was [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom#Knighthood|knighted]] in 1918 in recognition for his services to journalism. Le Sage retired from his post in June 1923 and died on New Year's Day, 1926, at his home in [[Fulham]].<ref>J. B. Firth, ''rev''. Joseph Coohill, \"Le Sage, Sir John Merry (1837-1926)\", in ''The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', H.C.G. Matthew and Brian Harrison, eds. (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2004), vol. 33, pgs. 414-415.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Edwin Arnold]] | title=Editor of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''| years=1888\u20131923| after=[[Frederick Miller (British journalist)|Frederick Miller]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Le Sage, John Merry}}\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n\n[[Category:British newspaper editors]]\n[[Category:1837 births]]\n[[Category:1926 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_le_Sage"}
